# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Array processing metrics are often assessed in noisy environments.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The model for noise may be either one of spatially incoherent noise, or one with interfering signals following the same propagation physics.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Estimation theory is an important and basic part of signal processing field, which used to deal with estimation problem in which the values of several parameters of the system should be estimated based on measured/empirical data that has a random component.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] As the number of applications increases, estimating temporal and spatial parameters become more important.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Array processing emerged in the last few decades as an active area and was centered on the ability of using and combining data from different sensors (antennas) in order to deal with specific estimation task (spatial and temporal processing).
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In addition to the information that can be extracted from the collected data the framework uses the advantage prior knowledge about the geometry of the sensor array to perform the estimation task.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Array processing is used in radar, sonar, seismic exploration, anti-jamming and wireless communications.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] One of the main advantages of using array processing along with an array of sensors is a smaller foot-print.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The problems associated with array processing include the number of sources used, their direction of arrivals, and their signal waveforms.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] There are four assumptions in array processing.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The first assumption is that there is uniform propagation in all directions of isotropic and non-dispersive medium.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The second assumption is that for far field array processing, the radius of propagation is much greater than size of the array and that there is plane wave propagation.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The third assumption is that there is a zero mean white noise and signal, which shows uncorrelation.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Finally, the last assumption is that there is no coupling and the calibration is perfect.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The ultimate goal of sensor array signal processing is to estimate the values of parameters by using available temporal and spatial information, collected through sampling a wavefield with a set of antennas that have a precise geometry description.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The processing of the captured data and information is done under the assumption that the wavefield is generated by a finite number of signal sources (emitters), and contains information about signal parameters characterizing and describing the sources.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] There are many applications related to the above problem formulation, where the number of sources, their directions and locations should be specified.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] To motivate the reader, some of the most important applications related to array processing will be discussed.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] array processing concept was closely linked to radar and sonar systems which represent the classical applications of array processing.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The antenna array is used in these systems to determine location(s) of source(s), cancel interference, suppress ground clutter.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] **Radar systems** used basically to detect objects by using radio waves.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The range, altitude, speed and direction of objects can be specified.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Radar systems started as military equipments then entered the civilian world.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In radar applications, different modes can be used, one of these modes is the active mode.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In this mode the antenna array based system radiates pulses and listens for the returns.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] By using the returns, the estimation of parameters such as velocity, range and DOAs (direction of arrival) of target of interest become possible.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Using the passive far-field listening arrays, only the DOAs can be estimated.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] **Sonar systems** (Sound Navigation and Ranging) use the sound waves that propagate under the water to detect objects on or under the water surface.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Two types of sonar systems can be defined the active one and the passive one.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In active sonar, the system emits pulses of sound and listens to the returns that will be used to estimate parameters.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In the passive sonar, the system is essentially listening for the sounds made by the target objects.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] There is a difference between the radar system that uses radio waves and the sonar system that uses sound waves, the reason why the sonar uses the sound wave is because sound waves travel farther in the water than do radar and light waves.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In passive sonar, the receiving array has the capability of detecting distant objects and their locations.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Deformable array are usually used in sonar systems where the antenna is typically drawn under the water.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In active sonar, the sonar system emits sound waves (acoustic energy) then listening and monitoring any existing echo (the reflected waves).
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The reflected sound waves can be used to estimate parameters, such as velocity, position and direction etc.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Difficulties and limitations in sonar systems comparing to radar systems emerged from the fact that the propagation speed of sound waves under the water is slower than the radio waves.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Another source of limitation is the high propagation losses and scattering.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Despite all these limitations and difficulties, sonar system remains a reliable technique for range, distance, position and other parameters estimation for underwater applications.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] NORSAR is an independent geo-scientific research facility that was founded in Norway in 1968.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] NORSAR has been working with array processing ever since to measure seismic activity around the globe.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] They are currently working on an International Monitoring System which will comprise 50 primary and 120 auxiliary seismic stations around the world.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] NORSAR has ongoing work to improve array processing to improve monitoring of seismic activity not only in Norway but around the globe.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Communication can be defined as the process of exchanging of information between two or more parties.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The last two decades witnessed a rapid growth of wireless communication systems.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] This success is a result of advances in communication theory and low power dissipation design process.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In general, communication (telecommunication) can be done by technological means through either electrical signals (wired communication) or electromagnetic waves (wireless communication).
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Antenna arrays have emerged as a support technology to increase the usage efficiency of spectral and enhance the accuracy of wireless communication systems by utilizing spatial dimension in addition to the classical time and frequency dimensions.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Array processing and estimation techniques have been used in wireless communication.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] During the last decade these techniques were re-explored as ideal candidates to be the solution for numerous problems in wireless communication.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In wireless communication, problems that affect quality and performance of the system may come from different sources.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The multiuser –medium multiple access- and multipath -signal propagation over multiple scattering paths in wireless channels- communication model is one of the most widespread communication models in wireless communication (mobile communication).
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In the case of multiuser communication environment, the existence of multiuser increases the inter-user interference possibility that can affect quality and performance of the system adversely.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In mobile communication systems the multipath problem is one of the basic problems that base stations have to deal with.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Base stations have been using spatial diversity for combating fading due to the severe multipath.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Base stations use an antenna array of several elements to achieve higher selectivity, so called beamforming.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Receiving array can be directed in the direction of one user at a time, while avoiding the interference from other users.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Array processing techniques got on much attention from medical and industrial applications.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In medical applications, the medical image processing field was one of the basic fields that use array processing.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Other medical applications that use array processing: diseases treatment, tracking waveforms that have information about the condition of internal organs e.g. the heart, localizing and analyzing brain activity by using bio-magnetic sensor arrays.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Speech enhancement and processing represents another field that has been affected by the new era of array processing.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Most of the acoustic front end systems became fully automatic systems (e.g. telephones).
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] However, the operational environment of these systems contains a mix of other acoustic sources; external noises as well as acoustic couplings of loudspeaker signals overwhelm and attenuate the desired speech signal.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In addition to these external sources, the strength of the desired signal is reduced due to the relatively distance between speaker and microphones.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Array processing techniques have opened new opportunities in speech processing to attenuate noise and echo without degrading the quality of and affecting adversely the speech signal.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In general array processing techniques can be used in speech processing to reduce the computing power (number of computations) and enhance the quality of the system (the performance).
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Representing the signal as a sum of sub-bands and adapting cancellation filters for the sub-band signals can reduce the demanded computation power and lead to a higher performance system.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Relying on multiple input channels allows designing systems of higher quality comparing to systems that use single channel and solving problems such as source localization, tracking and separation, which cannot be achieved in case of using single channel.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Astronomical environment contains a mix of external signals and noises that affect the quality of the desired signals.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Most of the arrays processing applications in astronomy are related to image processing.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The array used to achieve a higher quality that is not achievable by using a single channel.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The high image quality facilitates quantitative analysis and comparison with images at other wavelengths.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In general, astronomy arrays can be divided into two classes: the beamforming class and the correlation class.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Correlation arrays provide images over the entire single-element primary beam pattern, computed off-line from records of all the possible correlations between the antennas, pairwise.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In order to solve this problem (to guarantee that there is a valid solution) do we have to add conditions or assumptions on the operational environment and\or the used model?
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Since there are many parameters used to specify the system like the number of sources, the number of array elements ...etc. are there conditions that should be met first?
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The set of any q steering vectors is linearly independent.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Isotropic and non-dispersive medium – Uniform propagation in all directions.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Zero mean white noise and signal, uncorrelated.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Throughout this survey, it will be assumed that the number of underlying signals, q, in the observed process is considered known.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] There are, however, good and consistent techniques for estimating this value even if it is not known.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In general, parameters estimation techniques can be classified into: **spectral based and parametric based methods**.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In the former, one forms some spectrum-like function of the parameter(s) of interest.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The locations of the highest (separated) peaks of the function in question are recorded as the DOA estimates.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Parametric techniques, on the other hand, require a simultaneous search for all parameters of interest.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The basic advantage of using the parametric approach comparing to the spectral based approach is the accuracy, albeit at the expense of an increased computational complexity.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Spectral based algorithmic solutions can be further classified into beamforming techniques and subspace-based techniques.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The first method used to specify and automatically localize the signal sources using antenna arrays was the beamforming technique.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The idea behind beamforming is very simple: steer the array in one direction at a time and measure the output power.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The steering locations where we have the maximum power yield the DOA estimates.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The array response is steered by forming a linear combination of the sensor outputs.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Different beamforming approaches correspond to different choices of the weighting vector **F**.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The advantages of using beamforming technique are the simplicity, easy to use and understand.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] While the disadvantage of using this technique is the low resolution.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Many spectral methods in the past have called upon the spectral decomposition of a covariance matrix to carry out the analysis.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] A breakthrough came about when the eigen-structure of the covariance matrix was explicitly invoked, and its intrinsic properties were directly used to provide a solution to an underlying estimation problem for a given observed process.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] A class of spatial spectral estimation techniques is based on the eigen-value decomposition of the spatial covariance matrix.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The rationale behind this approach is that one wants to emphasize the choices for the steering vector a(θ) which correspond to signal directions.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The method exploits the property that the directions of arrival determine the eigen structure of the matrix.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The tremendous interest in the subspace based methods is mainly due to the introduction of the MUSIC (Multiple Signal Classification) algorithm.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] MUSIC was originally presented as a DOA estimator, then it has been successfully brought back to the spectral analysis/system identification problem with its later development.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] MUSIC spectrum approaches use a single realization of the stochastic process that is represent by the snapshots x (t), t=1, 2 ...M.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] MUSIC estimates are consistent and they converge to true source bearings as the number of snapshots grows to infinity.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] A basic drawback of MUSIC approach is its sensitivity to model errors.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] A costly procedure of calibration is required in MUSIC and it is very sensitive to errors in the calibration procedure.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The cost of calibration increases as the number of parameters that define the array manifold increases.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] While the spectral-based methods presented in the previous section are computationally attractive, they do not always yield sufficient accuracy.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In particular, for the cases when we have highly correlated signals, the performance of spectral-based methods may be insufficient.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] An alternative is to more fully exploit the underlying data model, leading to so-called parametric array processing methods.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The cost of using such methods to increase the efficiency is that the algorithms typically require a multidimensional search to find the estimates.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The most common used model based approach in signal processing is the maximum likelihood (ML) technique.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] This method requires a statistical framework for the data generation process.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] When applying the ML technique to the array processing problem, two main methods have been considered depending on the signal data model assumption.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] According to the Stochastic ML, the signals are modeled as Gaussian random processes.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] On the other hand, in the Deterministic ML the signals are considered as unknown, deterministic quantities that need to be estimated in conjunction with the direction of arrival.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The stochastic maximum likelihood method is obtained by modeling the signal waveforms as a Gaussian random process under the assumption that the process x(t) is a stationary, zero-mean, Gaussian process that is completely described by its second-order covariance matrix.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] This model is a reasonable one if the measurements are obtained by filtering wide-band signals using a narrow band-pass filter.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] While the background and receiver noise in the assumed data model can be thought of as emanating from a large number of independent noise sources, the same is usually not the case for the emitter signals.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] It therefore appears natural to model the noise as a stationary Gaussian white random process whereas the signal waveforms are deterministic (arbitrary) and unknown.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] According to the Deterministic ML the signals are considered as unknown, deterministic quantities that need to be estimated in conjunction with the direction of arrival.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] This is a natural model for digital communication applications where the signals are far from being normal random variables, and where estimation of the signal is of equal interest.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The problem of computing pairwise correlation as a function of frequency can be solved by two mathematically equivalent but distinct ways.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] By using Discrete Fourier Transform (DFT) it is possible to analyze signals in the time domain as well as in the spectral domain.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The first approach is "XF" correlation because it first cross-correlates antennas (the "X" operation) using a time-domain "lag" convolution, and then computes the spectrum (the "F" operation) for each resulting baseline.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The second approach "FX" takes advantage of the fact that convolution is equivalent to multiplication in Fourier domain.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] It first computes the spectrum for each individual antenna (the F operation), and then multiplies pairwise all antennas for each spectral channel (the X operation).
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] A FX correlator has an advantage over a XF correlators in that the computational complexity is O(N2).
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Therefore, FX correlators are more efficient for larger arrays.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Correlation spectrometers like the Michelson interferometer vary the time lag between signals obtain the power spectrum of input signals.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Cross-correlation spectroscopy with spatial interferometry, is possible by simply substituting a signal with voltage $V_{Y}(t)$ in equation **Eq.II** to produce the cross-correlation $R_{\text{XY}}(\tau )$ and the cross-spectrum $S_{\text{XY}}(f)$ .
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In radio astronomy, RF interference must be mitigated to detect and observe any meaningful objects and events in the night sky.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] where $\mathbf {R} _{v}$ is the visibilities covariance matrix (sources), $\sigma _{s}^{2}$ is the power of the interferer, and $\sigma _{n}^{2}$ is the noise power, and $\dagger$ denotes the Hermitian transpose.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] One can construct a projection matrix $\mathbf {P} _{a}^{\perp }$ , which, when left and right multiplied by the signal covariance matrix, will reduce the interference term to zero.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Since $\mathbf {a}$ is generally not known, $\mathbf {P} _{a}^{\perp }$ can be constructed using the eigen-decomposition of $\mathbf {R}$ , in particular the matrix containing an orthonormal basis of the noise subspace, which is the orthogonal complement of $\mathbf {a}$ .
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] The disadvantages to this approach include altering the visibilities covariance matrix and coloring the white noise term.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] This scheme attempts to make the interference-plus-noise term spectrally white.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] To do this, left and right multiply $\mathbf {R}$ with inverse square root factors of the interference-plus-noise terms.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] This approach requires much more computationally intensive matrix manipulations, and again the visibilities covariance matrix is altered.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] This scheme requires an accurate estimation of the interference term, but does not alter the noise or sources term.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Array processing technique represents a breakthrough in signal processing.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Many applications and problems which are solvable using array processing techniques are introduced.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In addition to these applications within the next few years the number of applications that include a form of array signal processing will increase.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] In this article we emphasized the importance of array processing by listing the most important applications that include a form of array processing techniques.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] We briefly describe the different classifications of array processing, spectral and parametric based approaches.
[src:vector-processor/array-processing] Some of the most important algorithms are covered, the advantage(s) and the disadvantage(s) of these algorithms also explained and discussed.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The **Cray-1** was a supercomputer designed, manufactured and marketed by Cray Research.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Announced in 1975, the first Cray-1 system was installed at Los Alamos National Laboratory in 1976.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Eventually, eighty Cray-1s were sold, making it one of the most successful supercomputers in history.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] It is perhaps best known for its unique shape, a relatively small C-shaped cabinet with a ring of benches around the outside covering the power supplies and the cooling system.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The Cray-1 was the first supercomputer to successfully implement the vector processor design.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] These systems improve the performance of math operations by arranging memory and registers to quickly perform a single operation on a large set of data.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Previous systems like the CDC STAR-100 and ASC had implemented these concepts but did so in a way that seriously limited their performance.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The Cray-1 addressed these problems and produced a machine that ran several times faster than any similar design.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The Cray-1's architect was Seymour Cray; the chief engineer was Cray Research co-founder Lester Davis.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] They would go on to design several new machines using the same basic concepts, and retained the performance crown into the 1990s.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] From 1968 to 1972, Seymour Cray of Control Data Corporation (CDC) worked on the CDC 8600, the successor to his earlier CDC 6600 and CDC 7600 designs.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The 8600 was essentially made up of four 7600s in a box with an additional special mode that allowed them to operate lock-step in a SIMD fashion.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Jim Thornton, formerly Cray's engineering partner on earlier designs, had started a more radical project known as the CDC STAR-100.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Unlike the 8600's brute-force approach to performance, the STAR took an entirely different route.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The main processor of the STAR had lower performance than the 7600, but added hardware and instructions to speed up particularly common supercomputer tasks.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] By 1972, the 8600 had reached a dead end; the machine was so incredibly complex that it was impossible to get one working properly.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Even a single faulty component would render the machine non-operational.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Cray went to William Norris, Control Data's CEO, saying that a redesign from scratch was needed.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] At the time, the company was in serious financial trouble, and with the STAR in the pipeline as well, Norris could not invest the money.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] As a result, Cray left CDC and started Cray Research very close to the CDC lab.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] In the back yard of the land he purchased in Chippewa Falls, Wisconsin, Cray and a group of former CDC employees started looking for ideas.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] At first, the concept of building another supercomputer seemed impossible, but after Cray Research's Chief Technology Officer travelled to Wall Street and found a lineup of investors willing to back Cray, all that was needed was a design.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] For four years Cray Research designed its first computer.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] In 1975 the 80 MHz Cray-1 was announced.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The excitement was so high that a bidding war for the first machine broke out between Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory and Los Alamos National Laboratory, the latter eventually winning and receiving serial number 001 in 1976 for a six-month trial.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The National Center for Atmospheric Research (NCAR) was the first official customer of Cray Research in 1977, paying US$8.86 million ($7.9 million plus $1 million for the disks) for serial number 3.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The NCAR machine was decommissioned in 1989.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The company expected to sell perhaps a dozen of the machines, and set the selling price accordingly, but ultimately over 80 Cray-1s of all types were sold, priced from $5M to $8M.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The machine made Seymour Cray a celebrity and his company a success, lasting until the supercomputer crash in the early 1990s.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Based on a recommendation by William Perry's study, the NSA purchased a Cray-1 for theoretical research in cryptanalysis.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The 160 MFLOPS Cray-1 was succeeded in 1982 by the 800 MFLOPS Cray X-MP, the first Cray multi-processing computer.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] In 1985, the very advanced Cray-2, capable of 1.9 GFLOPS peak performance, succeeded the first two models but met a somewhat limited commercial success because of certain problems at producing sustained performance in real-world applications.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Typical scientific workloads consist of reading in large data sets, transforming them in some way and then writing them back out again.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Normally the transformations being applied are identical across all of the data points in the set.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] For instance, the program might add 5 to every number in a set of a million numbers.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] In simple computers the program would loop over all million numbers, adding five, thereby executing a million instructions saying `a = add b, c`.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Internally the computer solves this instruction in several steps.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] First it reads the instruction from memory and decodes it, then it collects any additional information it needs, in this case the numbers b and c, and then finally runs the operation and stores the results.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The end result is that the computer requires tens or hundreds of millions of cycles to carry out these operations.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] In the STAR, new instructions essentially wrote the loops for the user.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The user told the machine where in memory the list of numbers was stored, then fed in a single instruction `a(1..1000000) = addv b(1..1000000), c(1..1000000)`.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] At first glance it appears the savings are limited; in this case the machine fetches and decodes only a single instruction instead of 1,000,000, thereby saving 1,000,000 fetches and decodes, perhaps one-fourth of the overall time.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Internally, the CPU of the computer is built up from a number of separate parts dedicated to a single task, for instance, adding a number, or fetching from memory.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Normally, as the instruction flows through the machine, only one part is active at any given time.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] This means that each sequential step of the entire process must complete before a result can be saved.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The addition of an instruction pipeline changes this.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] In such machines the CPU will "look ahead" and begin fetching succeeding instructions while the current instruction is still being processed.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] In this assembly line fashion any one instruction still requires as long to complete, but as soon as it finishes executing, the next instruction is right behind it, with most of the steps required for its execution already completed.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Vector processors use this technique with one additional trick.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Because the data layout is in a known format — a set of numbers arranged sequentially in memory — the pipelines can be tuned to improve the performance of fetches.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] On the receipt of a vector instruction, special hardware sets up the memory access for the arrays and stuffs the data into the processor as fast as possible.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] CDC's approach in the STAR used what is today known as a *memory-memory architecture*.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] This referred to the way the machine gathered data.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] It set up its pipeline to read from and write to memory directly.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] This allowed the STAR to use vectors of length not limited by the length of registers, making it highly flexible.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Unfortunately, the pipeline had to be very long in order to allow it to have enough instructions in flight to make up for the slow memory.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] That meant the machine incurred a high cost when switching from processing vectors to performing operations on non-vector operands.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Additionally, the low scalar performance of the machine meant that after the switch had taken place and the machine was running scalar instructions, the performance was quite poor.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The result was rather disappointing real-world performance, something that could, perhaps, have been forecast by Amdahl's law.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Cray studied the failure of the STAR and learned from it.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] He decided that in addition to fast vector processing, his design would also require excellent all-around scalar performance.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] That way when the machine switched modes, it would still provide superior performance.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Additionally he noticed that the workloads could be dramatically improved in most cases through the use of registers.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Just as earlier machines had ignored the fact that most operations were being applied to many data points, the STAR ignored the fact that those same data points would be repeatedly operated on.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Whereas the STAR would read and process the same memory five times to apply five vector operations on a set of data, it would be much faster to read the data into the CPU's registers once, and then apply the five operations.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] However, there were limitations with this approach.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Registers were significantly more expensive in terms of circuitry, so only a limited number could be provided.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] This implied that Cray's design would have less flexibility in terms of vector sizes.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Instead of reading any sized vector several times as in the STAR, the Cray-1 would have to read only a portion of the vector at a time, but it could then run several operations on that data prior to writing the results back to memory.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Given typical workloads, Cray felt that the small cost incurred by being required to break large sequential memory accesses into segments was a cost well worth paying.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Since the typical vector operation would involve loading a small set of data into the vector registers and then running several operations on it, the vector system of the new design had its own separate pipeline.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] For instance, the multiplication and addition units were implemented as separate hardware, so the results of one could be internally pipelined into the next, the instruction decode having already been handled in the machine's main pipeline.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Cray referred to this concept as *chaining*, as it allowed programmers to "chain together" several instructions and extract higher performance.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] In 1978, a team from the Argonne National Laboratory tested a variety of typical workloads on a Cray-1 as part of a proposal to purchase one for their use, replacing their IBM 370/195.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] They also planned on testing on the CDC STAR-100 and Burroughs Scientific Computer, but such tests, if they were performed, were not published.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The tests were run on the Cray-1 at the National Center for Atmospheric Research (NCAR) in Boulder, Colorado.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The only other Cray available at the time was the one at Los Alamos, but accessing this machine required Q clearance.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The first was a minimum conversion needed to get the program running without errors, but making no attempt to take advantage of the Cray's vectorization.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The second included a moderate set of updates to the code, often unwinding loops so they could be vectorized.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Generally, the minimal conversions ran roughly the same speed as the 370 to about 2 times its performance (mostly due to a larger exponent range on the Cray), but vectorization led to further increases between 2.5 and 10 times.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] In one example program, which performed an internal fast Fourier transform, performance improved from the IBM's 47 milliseconds to 3.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The new machine was the first Cray design to use integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Although ICs had been available since the 1960s, it was only in the early 1970s that they reached the performance necessary for high-speed applications.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] These integrated circuits were supplied by Fairchild Semiconductor and Motorola.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] In all, the Cray-1 contained about 200,000 gates.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] ICs were mounted on large five-layer printed circuit boards, with up to 144 ICs per board.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Boards were then mounted back to back for cooling (see below) and placed in twenty-four 28-inch-high (710 mm) racks containing 72 double-boards.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The typical module (distinct processing unit) required one or two boards.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] In all the machine contained 1,662 modules in 113 varieties.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Each cable between the modules was a twisted pair, cut to a specific length in order to guarantee the signals arrived at precisely the right time and minimize electrical reflection.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Each signal produced by the ECL circuitry was a differential pair, so the signals were balanced.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] This tended to make the demand on the power supply more constant and reduce switching noise.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The load on the power supply was so evenly balanced that Cray boasted that the power supply was unregulated.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] To the power supply, the entire computer system looked like a simple resistor.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The high-performance ECL circuitry generated considerable heat, and Cray's designers spent as much effort on the design of the refrigeration system as they did on the rest of the mechanical design.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] In this case, each circuit board was paired with a second, placed back to back with a sheet of copper between them.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The copper sheet conducted heat to the edges of the cage, where liquid Freon running in stainless steel pipes drew it away to the cooling unit below the machine.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The first Cray-1 was delayed six months due to problems in the cooling system; lubricant that is normally mixed with the Freon to keep the compressor running would leak through the seals and eventually coat the boards with oil until they shorted out.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] New welding techniques had to be used to properly seal the tubing.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] In order to bring maximum speed out of the machine, the entire chassis was bent into a large C-shape.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Speed-dependent portions of the system were placed on the "inside edge" of the chassis, where the wire-lengths were shorter.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] This allowed the cycle time to be decreased to 12.5 ns (80 MHz), not as fast as the 8 ns 8600 he had given up on, but fast enough to beat CDC 7600 and the STAR.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] NCAR estimated that the overall throughput on the system was 4.5 times that of the CDC 7600.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The Cray-1 was built as a 64-bit system, a departure from the 7600/6600, which were 60-bit machines (a change was also planned for the 8600).
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Addressing was 24-bit, with a maximum of 1,048,576 64-bit words (1 megaword) of main memory, where each word also had eight parity bits for a total of 72 bits per word.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Memory was spread across 16 interleaved memory banks, each with a 50 ns cycle time, allowing up to four words to be read per cycle.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Smaller configurations could have 0.25 or 0.5 megawords of main memory.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Maximum aggregate memory bandwidth was 638 Mbit/s.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The main register set consisted of eight 64-bit scalar (S) registers and eight 24-bit address (A) registers.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] These were backed by a set of sixty-four registers each for S and A temporary storage known as T and B respectively, which could not be seen by the functional units.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The vector system added another eight 64-element by 64-bit vector (V) registers, as well as a vector length (VL) and vector mask (VM).
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Finally, the system also included a 64-bit real-time clock register and four 64-bit instruction buffers that held sixty-four 16-bit instructions each.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The hardware was set up to allow the vector registers to be fed at one word per cycle, while the address and scalar registers required two cycles.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] In contrast, the entire 16-word instruction buffer could be filled in four cycles.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The Cray-1 had twelve pipelined functional units.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The 24-bit address arithmetic was performed in an add unit and a multiply unit.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The scalar portion of the system consisted of an add unit, a logical unit, a population count, a leading zero count unit and a shift unit.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The vector portion consisted of add, logical and shift units.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The floating point functional units were shared between the scalar and vector portions, and these consisted of add, multiply and reciprocal approximation units.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] It could issue one instruction per clock cycle, for a theoretical performance of 80 MIPS, but with vector floating-point multiplication and addition occurring in parallel theoretical performance was 160 MFLOPS.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Since the machine was designed to operate on large data sets, the design also dedicated considerable circuitry to I/O.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Earlier Cray designs at CDC had included separate computers dedicated to this task, but this was no longer needed.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Instead the Cray-1 included four six-channel controllers, each of which was given access to main memory once every four cycles.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The channels were 16 bits wide and included three control bits and four bits for error correction, so the maximum transfer speed was one word per 100 ns, or 500 thousand words per second for the entire machine.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The initial model, the **Cray-1A**, weighed 10,500 pounds (4,800 kg) including the Freon refrigeration system.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Configured with 1 million words of main memory, the machine and its power supplies consumed about 115 kW of power; cooling and storage likely more than doubled this figure.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] A Data General SuperNova S/200 minicomputer served as the maintenance control unit (MCU), which was used to feed the Cray Operating System into the system at boot time, to monitor the CPU during use, and optionally as a front-end computer.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Most, if not all, Cray-1As were delivered using the follow-on Data General Eclipse as the MCU.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The reliability of the CRAY-1A was very low by today's standards.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] At the European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts, which was one of the first customers, the mean time between hardware faults was reported to be 96 hours in 1979.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Seymour Cray deliberately made design decisions that sacrificed reliability for speed, but improved his later designs after being questioned on this matter.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Similarly, the Cray Operating System (COS) was fairly rudimentary, hardly tested and updated weekly or even daily in the early days.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The **Cray-1S**, announced in 1979, was an improved Cray-1 that supported a larger main memory of 1, 2 or 4 million words.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The larger main memory was made possible through the use of 4,096 x 1-bit bipolar RAM ICs with a 25 ns access time.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The Data General minicomputers were optionally replaced with an in-house 16-bit design.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The I/O subsystem was separated from the main machine, connected to the main system via a 6 Mbit/s control channel and a 100 Mbit/s High Speed Data Channel.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] This separation made the 1S look like two "half Crays" separated by a few feet, which allowed the I/O system to be expanded as needed.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Systems could be bought in a variety of configurations from the S/500 with no I/O and 0.5 million words of memory to the S/4400 with four I/O processors and 4 million words of memory.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The **Cray-1M**, announced in 1982, replaced the Cray-1S.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] It had a faster 12 ns cycle time and used less expensive MOS RAM in the main memory.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The 1M was supplied in only three versions, the M/1200 with 1 million words in 8 banks, or the M/2200 and M/4200 with 2 or 4 million words in 16 banks.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] All of these machines included two, three or four I/O processors, and the system added an optional second High Speed Data Channel.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Users could add a Solid-state Storage Device with 8 to 32 million words of MOS RAM.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] CTSS was written in a dynamic memory Fortran, first named LRLTRAN, which ran on CDC 7600s, renamed CVC (pronounced "Civic") when vectorization for the Cray-1 was added.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Cray Research attempted to support these sites accordingly.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] These software choices had influences on later minisupercomputers, also known as "crayettes".
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] NCAR has its own operating system (NCAROS).
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Libraries started with Cray Research's own offerings and Netlib.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Other operating systems existed, but most languages tended to be Fortran or Fortran-based.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Bell Laboratories, as proof of both portability concept and circuit design, moved the first C compiler to their Cray-1 (non-vectorizing).
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] This act would later give CRI a six-month head start on the Cray-2 Unix port to ETA Systems' detriment, and Lucasfilm's first computer generated test film, *The Adventures of André & Wally B.*.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Application software generally tends to be either classified (*e.g.* nuclear code, cryptanalytic code) or proprietary (*e.g.* petroleum reservoir modeling).
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] This was because little software was shared between customers and university customers.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The few exceptions were climatological and meteorological programs until the NSF responded to the Japanese Fifth Generation Computer Systems project and created its supercomputer centers.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] Partly because Cray were interested in the publicity, they supported the development of Cray Blitz which won the fourth (1983) and fifth (1986) World Computer Chess Championship, as well as the 1983 and 1984 North American Computer Chess Championship.
[src:vector-processor/cray-1] The program, Chess, that dominated in the 1970s ran on Control Data Corporation supercomputers.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] In computer science, **parallelism** and concurrency are two different things: a parallel program uses multiple CPU cores, each core performing a task independently.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] On the other hand, concurrency enables a program to deal with multiple tasks even on a single CPU core; the core switches between tasks (i.e. threads) without necessarily completing each one.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] A program can have both, neither or a combination of parallelism and concurrency characteristics.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism, with multi-core and multi-processor computers having multiple processing elements within a single machine, while clusters, MPPs, and grids use multiple computers to work on the same task.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Specialized parallel computer architectures are sometimes used alongside traditional processors, for accelerating specific tasks.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Communication and synchronization between the different subtasks are typically some of the greatest obstacles to getting optimal parallel program performance.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] A theoretical upper bound on the speed-up of a single program as a result of parallelization is given by Amdahl's law, which states that it is limited by the fraction of time for which the parallelization can be utilised.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Traditionally, computer software has been written for serial computation.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] To solve a problem, an algorithm is constructed and implemented as a serial stream of instructions.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] These instructions are executed on a central processing unit on one computer.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Only one instruction may execute at a time—after that instruction is finished, the next one is executed.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Parallel computing, on the other hand, uses multiple processing elements simultaneously to solve a problem.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] This is accomplished by breaking the problem into independent parts so that each processing element can execute its part of the algorithm simultaneously with the others.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The processing elements can be diverse and include resources such as a single computer with multiple processors, several networked computers, specialized hardware, or any combination of the above.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Historically parallel computing was used for scientific computing and the simulation of scientific problems, particularly in the natural and engineering sciences, such as meteorology.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] This led to the design of parallel hardware and software, and high performance computing.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Frequency scaling was the dominant reason for improvements in computer performance from the mid-1980s until 2004.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The runtime of a program is equal to the number of instructions multiplied by the average time per instruction.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Maintaining everything else constant, increasing the clock frequency decreases the average time it takes to execute an instruction.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] An increase in frequency thus decreases runtime for all compute-bound programs.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] However, power consumption *P* by a chip is given by the equation *P* = *C* × *V* 2 × *F*, where *C* is the capacitance being switched per clock cycle (proportional to the number of transistors whose inputs change), *V* is voltage, and *F* is the processor frequency (cycles per second).
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Increases in frequency increase the amount of power used in a processor.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Increasing processor power consumption led ultimately to Intel's May 8, 2004 cancellation of its Tejas and Jayhawk processors, which is generally cited as the end of frequency scaling as the dominant computer architecture paradigm.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] To deal with the problem of power consumption and overheating the major central processing unit (CPU or processor) manufacturers started to produce power efficient processors with multiple cores.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The core is the computing unit of the processor and in multi-core processors each core is independent and can access the same memory concurrently.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Multi-core processors have brought parallel computing to desktop computers.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Thus parallelization of serial programs has become a mainstream programming task.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] In 2012 quad-core processors became standard for desktop computers, while servers had 10+ core processors.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Moore's law predicted that the number of cores per processor would double every 18–24 months.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] By 2023 some processors had over one hundred cores.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Some designs having a mix of performance and efficiency cores (such as ARM's big.LITTLE design) due to thermal and design constraints.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] An operating system can ensure that different tasks and user programs are run in parallel on the available cores.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] However, for a serial software program to take full advantage of the multi-core architecture the programmer needs to restructure and parallelize the code.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] A speed-up of application software runtime will no longer be achieved through frequency scaling, instead programmers will need to parallelize their software code to take advantage of the increasing computing power of multicore architectures.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Optimally, the speedup from parallelization would be linear—doubling the number of processing elements should halve the runtime, and doubling it a second time should again halve the runtime.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] However, very few parallel algorithms achieve optimal speedup.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Most of them have a near-linear speedup for small numbers of processing elements, which flattens out into a constant value for large numbers of processing elements.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The maximum potential speedup of an overall system can be calculated by Amdahl's law.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law indicates that optimal performance improvement is achieved by balancing enhancements to both parallelizable and non-parallelizable components of a task.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Furthermore, it reveals that increasing the number of processors yields diminishing returns, with negligible speedup gains beyond a certain point.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law has limitations, including assumptions of fixed workload, neglecting inter-process communication and synchronization overheads, primarily focusing on computational aspect and ignoring extrinsic factors such as data persistence, I/O operations, and memory access overheads.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Gustafson's law and Universal Scalability Law give a more realistic assessment of the parallel performance.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Understanding data dependencies is fundamental in implementing parallel algorithms.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] No program can run more quickly than the longest chain of dependent calculations (known as the critical path), since calculations that depend upon prior calculations in the chain must be executed in order.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] However, most algorithms do not consist of just a long chain of dependent calculations; there are usually opportunities to execute independent calculations in parallel.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Let *P**i* and *P**j* be two program segments.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions describe when the two are independent and can be executed in parallel.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] For *P**i*, let *I**i* be all of the input variables and *O**i* the output variables, and likewise for *P**j*.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Violation of the first condition introduces a flow dependency, corresponding to the first segment producing a result used by the second segment.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The second condition represents an anti-dependency, when the second segment produces a variable needed by the first segment.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The third and final condition represents an output dependency: when two segments write to the same location, the result comes from the logically last executed segment.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] In this example, instruction 3 cannot be executed before (or even in parallel with) instruction 2, because instruction 3 uses a result from instruction 2.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] It violates condition 1, and thus introduces a flow dependency.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] In this example, there are no dependencies between the instructions, so they can all be run in parallel.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions do not allow memory to be shared between different processes.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] For that, some means of enforcing an ordering between accesses is necessary, such as semaphores, barriers or some other synchronization method.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Subtasks in a parallel program are often called threads.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Some parallel computer architectures use smaller, lightweight versions of threads known as fibers, while others use bigger versions known as processes.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] However, "threads" is generally accepted as a generic term for subtasks.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Threads will often need synchronized access to an object or other resource, for example when they must update a variable that is shared between them.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Without synchronization, the instructions between the two threads may be interleaved in any order.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] If instruction 1B is executed between 1A and 3A, or if instruction 1A is executed between 1B and 3B, the program will produce incorrect data.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The programmer must use a lock to provide mutual exclusion.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] A lock is a programming language construct that allows one thread to take control of a variable and prevent other threads from reading or writing it, until that variable is unlocked.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The thread holding the lock is free to execute its critical section (the section of a program that requires exclusive access to some variable), and to unlock the data when it is finished.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] One thread will successfully lock variable V, while the other thread will be locked out—unable to proceed until V is unlocked again.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] This guarantees correct execution of the program.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Locks may be necessary to ensure correct program execution when threads must serialize access to resources, but their use can greatly slow a program and may affect its reliability.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Locking multiple variables using non-atomic locks introduces the possibility of program deadlock.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] An atomic lock locks multiple variables all at once.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] If it cannot lock all of them, it does not lock any of them.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] If two threads each need to lock the same two variables using non-atomic locks, it is possible that one thread will lock one of them and the second thread will lock the second variable.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] In such a case, neither thread can complete, and deadlock results.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Many parallel programs require that their subtasks act in synchrony.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Barriers are typically implemented using a lock or a semaphore.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] One class of algorithms, known as lock-free and wait-free algorithms, altogether avoids the use of locks and barriers.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] However, this approach is generally difficult to implement and requires correctly designed data structures.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Not all parallelization results in speed-up.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Generally, as a task is split up into more and more threads, those threads spend an ever-increasing portion of their time communicating with each other or waiting on each other for access to resources.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Once the overhead from resource contention or communication dominates the time spent on other computation, further parallelization (that is, splitting the workload over even more threads) increases rather than decreases the amount of time required to finish.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] This problem, known as parallel slowdown, can be improved in some cases by software analysis and redesign.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Applications are often classified according to how often their subtasks need to synchronize or communicate with each other.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] An application exhibits fine-grained parallelism if its subtasks must communicate many times per second; it exhibits coarse-grained parallelism if they do not communicate many times per second, and it exhibits embarrassing parallelism if they rarely or never have to communicate.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Embarrassingly parallel applications are considered the easiest to parallelize.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Flynn created one of the earliest classification systems for parallel (and sequential) computers and programs, now known as Flynn's taxonomy.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Flynn classified programs and computers by whether they were operating using a single set or multiple sets of instructions, and whether or not those instructions were using a single set or multiple sets of data.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-single-data (SISD) classification is equivalent to an entirely sequential program.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-multiple-data (SIMD) classification is analogous to doing the same operation repeatedly over a large data set.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] This is commonly done in signal processing applications.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-single-data (MISD) is a rarely used classification.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] While computer architectures to deal with this were devised (such as systolic arrays), few applications that fit this class materialized.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-multiple-data (MIMD) programs are by far the most common type of parallel programs.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Hennessy, "Some machines are hybrids of these categories, of course, but this classic model has survived because it is simple, easy to understand, and gives a good first approximation.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can incur significant overhead in practice, primarily due to the costs associated with merging data from multiple processes.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Specifically, inter-process communication and synchronization can lead to overheads that are substantially higher—often by two or more orders of magnitude—compared to processing the same data on a single thread.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Therefore, the overall improvement should be carefully evaluated.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] From the advent of very-large-scale integration (VLSI) computer-chip fabrication technology in the 1970s until about 1986, speed-up in computer architecture was driven by doubling computer word size—the amount of information the processor can manipulate per cycle.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Increasing the word size reduces the number of instructions the processor must execute to perform an operation on variables whose sizes are greater than the length of the word.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Historically, 4-bit microprocessors were replaced with 8-bit, then 16-bit, then 32-bit microprocessors.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] This trend generally came to an end with the introduction of 32-bit processors, which has been a standard in general-purpose computing for two decades.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Not until the early 2000s, with the advent of x86-64 architectures, did 64-bit processors become commonplace.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] A computer program is, in essence, a stream of instructions executed by a processor.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Without instruction-level parallelism, a processor can only issue less than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC < 1).
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *subscalar* processors.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] These instructions can be re-ordered and combined into groups which are then executed in parallel without changing the result of the program.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] This is known as instruction-level parallelism.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Advances in instruction-level parallelism dominated computer architecture from the mid-1980s until the mid-1990s.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] All modern processors have multi-stage instruction pipelines.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Each stage in the pipeline corresponds to a different action the processor performs on that instruction in that stage; a processor with an *N*-stage pipeline can have up to *N* different instructions at different stages of completion and thus can issue one instruction per clock cycle (IPC = 1).
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *scalar* processors.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The canonical example of a pipelined processor is a RISC processor, with five stages: instruction fetch (IF), instruction decode (ID), execute (EX), memory access (MEM), and register write back (WB).
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The Pentium 4 processor had a 35-stage pipeline.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Most modern processors also have multiple execution units.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] They usually combine this feature with pipelining and thus can issue more than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC > 1).
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *superscalar* processors.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Superscalar processors differ from multi-core processors in that the several execution units are not entire processors (i.e. processing units).
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Instructions can be grouped together only if there is no data dependency between them.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Scoreboarding and the Tomasulo algorithm (which is similar to scoreboarding but makes use of register renaming) are two of the most common techniques for implementing out-of-order execution and instruction-level parallelism.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Task parallelisms is the characteristic of a parallel program that "entirely different calculations can be performed on either the same or different sets of data".
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] This contrasts with data parallelism, where the same calculation is performed on the same or different sets of data.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Task parallelism involves the decomposition of a task into sub-tasks and then allocating each sub-task to a processor for execution.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The processors would then execute these sub-tasks concurrently and often cooperatively.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Task parallelism does not usually scale with the size of a problem.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Superword level parallelism is a vectorization technique based on loop unrolling and basic block vectorization.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] It is distinct from loop vectorization algorithms in that it can exploit parallelism of inline code, such as manipulating coordinates, color channels or in loops unrolled by hand.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Main memory in a parallel computer is either shared memory (shared between all processing elements in a single address space), or distributed memory (in which each processing element has its own local address space).
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Distributed memory refers to the fact that the memory is logically distributed, but often implies that it is physically distributed as well.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Distributed shared memory and memory virtualization combine the two approaches, where the processing element has its own local memory and access to the memory on non-local processors.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Accesses to local memory are typically faster than accesses to non-local memory.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] On the supercomputers, distributed shared memory space can be implemented using the programming model such as PGAS.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] This model allows processes on one compute node to transparently access the remote memory of another compute node.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] All compute nodes are also connected to an external shared memory system via high-speed interconnect, such as Infiniband, this external shared memory system is known as burst buffer, which is typically built from arrays of non-volatile memory physically distributed across multiple I/O nodes.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Computer architectures in which each element of main memory can be accessed with equal latency and bandwidth are known as uniform memory access (UMA) systems.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Typically, that can be achieved only by a shared memory system, in which the memory is not physically distributed.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] A system that does not have this property is known as a non-uniform memory access (NUMA) architecture.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Distributed memory systems have non-uniform memory access.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Computer systems (with the exception of Groq's LPUs) make use of caches—small and fast memories located close to the processor which store temporary copies of memory values (nearby in both the physical and logical sense).
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Parallel computer systems have difficulties with caches that may store the same value in more than one location, with the possibility of incorrect program execution.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] These computers require a cache coherency system, which keeps track of cached values and strategically purges them, thus ensuring correct program execution.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Bus snooping is one of the most common methods for keeping track of which values are being accessed (and thus should be purged).
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Designing large, high-performance cache coherence systems is a very difficult problem in computer architecture.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] As a result, shared memory computer architectures do not scale and distributed memory systems do.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Parallel computers based on interconnected networks need to have some kind of routing to enable the passing of messages between nodes that are not directly connected.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The medium used for communication between the processors is likely to be hierarchical in large multiprocessor machines.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] This classification is broadly analogous to the distance between basic computing nodes.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] These are not mutually exclusive; for example, clusters of symmetric multiprocessors are relatively common.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] A multi-core processor is a processor that includes multiple processing units (called "cores") on the same chip.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] IBM's Cell microprocessor, designed for use in the Sony PlayStation 3, is a prominent multi-core processor.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Each core in a multi-core processor can potentially be superscalar as well—that is, on every clock cycle, each core can issue multiple instructions from one thread.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Simultaneous multithreading (of which Intel's Hyper-Threading is the best known) was an early form of pseudo-multi-coreism.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] A processor capable of concurrent multithreading includes multiple execution units in the same processing unit—that is it has a superscalar architecture—and can issue multiple instructions per clock cycle from *multiple* threads.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Temporal multithreading on the other hand includes a single execution unit in the same processing unit and can issue one instruction at a time from *multiple* threads.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] A symmetric multiprocessor (SMP) is a computer system with multiple identical processors that share memory and connect via a bus.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Bus contention prevents bus architectures from scaling.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] As a result, SMPs generally do not comprise more than 32 processors.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Because of the small size of the processors and the significant reduction in the requirements for bus bandwidth achieved by large caches, such symmetric multiprocessors are extremely cost-effective, provided that a sufficient amount of memory bandwidth exists.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] A distributed computer (also known as a distributed memory multiprocessor) is a distributed memory computer system in which the processing elements are connected by a network.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Distributed computers are highly scalable.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have a lot of overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] A cluster is a group of loosely coupled computers that work together closely, so that in some respects they can be regarded as a single computer.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Clusters are composed of multiple standalone machines connected by a network.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] While machines in a cluster do not have to be symmetric, load balancing is more difficult if they are not.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The most common type of cluster is the Beowulf cluster, which is a cluster implemented on multiple identical commercial off-the-shelf computers connected with a TCP/IP Ethernet local area network.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Beowulf technology was originally developed by Thomas Sterling and Donald Becker.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] 87% of all Top500 supercomputers are clusters.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The remaining are Massively Parallel Processors, explained below.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Because grid computing systems (described below) can easily handle embarrassingly parallel problems, modern clusters are typically designed to handle more difficult problems—problems that require nodes to share intermediate results with each other more often.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] This requires a high bandwidth and, more importantly, a low-latency interconnection network.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Many historic and current supercomputers use customized high-performance network hardware specifically designed for cluster computing, such as the Cray Gemini network.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] As of 2014, most current supercomputers use some off-the-shelf standard network hardware, often Myrinet, InfiniBand, or Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] A massively parallel processor (MPP) is a single computer with many networked processors.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] MPPs have many of the same characteristics as clusters, but MPPs have specialized interconnect networks (whereas clusters use commodity hardware for networking).
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] MPPs also tend to be larger than clusters, typically having "far more" than 100 processors.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] In an MPP, "each CPU contains its own memory and copy of the operating system and application.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] IBM's Blue Gene/L, the fifth fastest supercomputer in the world according to the June 2009 TOP500 ranking, is an MPP.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Grid computing is the most distributed form of parallel computing.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] It makes use of computers communicating over the Internet to work on a given problem.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Because of the low bandwidth and extremely high latency available on the Internet, distributed computing typically deals only with embarrassingly parallel problems.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Most grid computing applications use middleware (software that sits between the operating system and the application to manage network resources and standardize the software interface).
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The most common grid computing middleware is the Berkeley Open Infrastructure for Network Computing (BOINC).
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Often volunteer computing software makes use of "spare cycles", performing computations at times when a computer is idling.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The ubiquity of the Internet and high-bandwidth networks enabled cloud computing, a model where massively parallel resources are provided as a service.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] This paradigm abstracts the underlying hardware, allowing users to access virtualized clusters for scalable workloads without managing physical infrastructure.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Modern distributed ledger protocols apply parallel computing principles to overcome the sequential bottlenecks of traditional blockchains.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] By sharding the state space, newer consensus architectures allow for "massively parallel transaction processing".
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] In this model, utilized by protocols such as Cerberus, independent transactions are treated as parallel tasks that can be executed simultaneously on different nodes, rather than being processed serially in a single global block.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Within parallel computing, there are specialized parallel devices that remain niche areas of interest.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] While not domain-specific, they tend to be applicable to only a few classes of parallel problems.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Reconfigurable computing is the use of a field-programmable gate array (FPGA) as a co-processor to a general-purpose computer.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] An FPGA is, in essence, a computer chip that can rewire itself for a given task.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] FPGAs can be programmed with hardware description languages such as VHDL or Verilog.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Several vendors have created C to HDL languages that attempt to emulate the syntax and semantics of the C programming language, with which most programmers are familiar.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The best known C to HDL languages are Mitrion-C, Impulse C, and Handel-C.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Specific subsets of SystemC based on C++ can also be used for this purpose.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] AMD's decision to open its HyperTransport technology to third-party vendors has become the enabling technology for high-performance reconfigurable computing.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] General-purpose computing on graphics processing units (GPGPU) is a fairly recent trend in computer engineering research.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] GPUs are co-processors that have been heavily optimized for computer graphics processing.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Computer graphics processing is a field dominated by data parallel operations—particularly linear algebra matrix operations.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] In the early days, GPGPU programs used the normal graphics APIs for executing programs.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] However, several new programming languages and platforms have been built to do general purpose computation on GPUs with both Nvidia and AMD releasing programming environments with CUDA and Stream SDK respectively.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Other GPU programming languages include BrookGPU, PeakStream, and RapidMind.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Nvidia has also released specific products for computation in their Tesla series.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The technology consortium Khronos Group has released the OpenCL specification, which is a framework for writing programs that execute across platforms consisting of CPUs and GPUs.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] AMD, Apple, Intel, Nvidia and others are supporting OpenCL.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Several application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) approaches have been devised for dealing with parallel applications.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Because an ASIC is (by definition) specific to a given application, it can be fully optimized for that application.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] As a result, for a given application, an ASIC tends to outperform a general-purpose computer.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] However, ASICs are created by UV photolithography.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] This process requires a mask set, which can be extremely expensive.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] A mask set can cost over a million US dollars.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] (The smaller the transistors required for the chip, the more expensive the mask will be.) Meanwhile, performance increases in general-purpose computing over time (as described by Moore's law) tend to wipe out these gains in only one or two chip generations.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] High initial cost, and the tendency to be overtaken by Moore's-law-driven general-purpose computing, has rendered ASICs unfeasible for most parallel computing applications.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] One example is the PFLOPS RIKEN MDGRAPE-3 machine which uses custom ASICs for molecular dynamics simulation.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] A vector processor is a CPU or computer system that can execute the same instruction on large sets of data.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Vector processors have high-level operations that work on linear arrays of numbers or vectors.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] An example vector operation is *A* = *B* × *C*, where *A*, *B*, and *C* are each 64-element vectors of 64-bit floating-point numbers.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] They are closely related to Flynn's SIMD classification.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Cray computers became famous for their vector-processing computers in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] However, vector processors—both as CPUs and as full computer systems—have generally disappeared.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Modern processor instruction sets do include some vector processing instructions, such as with Freescale Semiconductor's AltiVec and Intel's Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE).
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Concurrent programming languages, libraries, APIs, and parallel programming models (such as algorithmic skeletons) have been created for programming parallel computers.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] These can generally be divided into classes based on the assumptions they make about the underlying memory architecture—shared memory, distributed memory, or shared distributed memory.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Shared memory programming languages communicate by manipulating shared memory variables.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Distributed memory uses message passing.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] POSIX Threads and OpenMP are two of the most widely used shared memory APIs, whereas Message Passing Interface (MPI) is the most widely used message-passing system API.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] One concept used in programming parallel programs is the future concept, where one part of a program promises to deliver a required datum to another part of a program at some future time.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Efforts to standardize parallel programming include an open standard called OpenHMPP for hybrid multi-core parallel programming.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The OpenHMPP directive-based programming model offers a syntax to efficiently offload computations on hardware accelerators and to optimize data movement to/from the hardware memory using remote procedure calls.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The rise of consumer GPUs has led to support for compute kernels, either in graphics APIs (referred to as compute shaders), in dedicated APIs (such as OpenCL), or in other language extensions.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Automatic parallelization of a sequential program by a compiler is the "holy grail" of parallel computing, especially with the aforementioned limit of processor frequency.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Despite decades of work by compiler researchers, automatic parallelization has had only limited success.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Mainstream parallel programming languages remain either explicitly parallel or (at best) partially implicit, in which a programmer gives the compiler directives for parallelization.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] A few fully implicit parallel programming languages exist—SISAL, Parallel Haskell, SequenceL, SystemC (for FPGAs), Mitrion-C, VHDL, and Verilog.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] As a computer system grows in complexity, the mean time between failures usually decreases.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing is a technique whereby the computer system takes a "snapshot" of the application—a record of all current resource allocations and variable states, akin to a core dump—; this information can be used to restore the program if the computer should fail.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing means that the program has to restart from only its last checkpoint rather than the beginning.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] While checkpointing provides benefits in a variety of situations, it is especially useful in highly parallel systems with a large number of processors used in high performance computing.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] As parallel computers become larger and faster, we are now able to solve problems that had previously taken too long to run.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Fields as varied as bioinformatics (for protein folding and sequence analysis) and economics have taken advantage of parallel computing.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can also be applied to the design of fault-tolerant computer systems, particularly via lockstep systems performing the same operation in parallel.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] This provides redundancy in case one component fails, and also allows automatic error detection and error correction if the results differ.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] These methods can be used to help prevent single-event upsets caused by transient errors.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Although additional measures may be required in embedded or specialized systems, this method can provide a cost-effective approach to achieve n-modular redundancy in commercial off-the-shelf systems.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The origins of true (MIMD) parallelism go back to Luigi Federico Menabrea and his *Sketch of the Analytic Engine Invented by Charles Babbage*.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] In 1957, Compagnie des Machines Bull announced the first computer architecture specifically designed for parallelism, the Gamma 60.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] It utilized a fork-join model and a "Program Distributor" to dispatch and collect data to and from independent processing units connected to a central memory.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] In April 1958, Stanley Gill (Ferranti) discussed parallel programming and the need for branching and waiting.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Also in 1958, IBM researchers John Cocke and Daniel Slotnick discussed the use of parallelism in numerical calculations for the first time.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Burroughs Corporation introduced the D825 in 1962, a four-processor computer that accessed up to 16 memory modules through a crossbar switch.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] In 1967, Amdahl and Slotnick published a debate about the feasibility of parallel processing at American Federation of Information Processing Societies Conference.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] It was during this debate that Amdahl's law was coined to define the limit of speed-up due to parallelism.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] In 1969, Honeywell introduced its first Multics system, a symmetric multiprocessor system capable of running up to eight processors in parallel.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] C.mmp, a multi-processor project at Carnegie Mellon University in the 1970s, was among the first multiprocessors with more than a few processors.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The first bus-connected multiprocessor with snooping caches was the Synapse N+1 in 1984.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] SIMD parallel computers can be traced back to the 1970s.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The motivation behind early SIMD computers was to amortize the gate delay of the processor's control unit over multiple instructions.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] In 1964, Slotnick had proposed building a massively parallel computer for the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] His design was funded by the US Air Force, which was the earliest SIMD parallel-computing effort, ILLIAC IV.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The key to its design was a fairly high parallelism, with up to 256 processors, which allowed the machine to work on large datasets in what would later be known as vector processing.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] However, ILLIAC IV was called "the most infamous of supercomputers", because the project was only one-fourth completed, but took 11 years and cost almost four times the original estimate.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] When it was finally ready to run its first real application in 1976, it was outperformed by existing commercial supercomputers such as the Cray-1.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] In the early 1970s, at the MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert started developing the *Society of Mind* theory, which views the biological brain as massively parallel computer.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] In 1986, Minsky published *The Society of Mind*, which claims that "mind is formed from many little agents, each mindless by itself".
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] The theory attempts to explain how what we call intelligence could be a product of the interaction of non-intelligent parts.
[src:vector-processor/parallel-computing] Minsky says that the biggest source of ideas about the theory came from his work in trying to create a machine that uses a robotic arm, a video camera, and a computer to build with children's blocks.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] In computer science, **stream processing** (also known as **event stream processing**, **data stream processing**, or **distributed stream processing**) is a programming paradigm which views streams, or sequences of events in time, as the central input and output objects of computation.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Stream processing encompasses dataflow programming, reactive programming, and distributed data processing.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Stream processing systems use streaming algorithms to trace parallel processing for data streams.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] The stream processing paradigm simplifies parallel software and hardware by restricting the parallel computation that can be performed.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Given a sequence of data (a *stream*), a series of operations (*kernel functions*) is applied to each element in the stream.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Kernel functions are usually pipelined, and optimal local on-chip memory reuse is attempted, in order to minimize the loss in bandwidth, associated with external memory interaction.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] *Uniform streaming*, where one kernel function is applied to all elements in the stream, is typical.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Since the kernel and stream abstractions expose data dependencies, compiler tools can fully automate and optimize on-chip management tasks.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Stream processing hardware can use scoreboarding, for example, to initiate a direct memory access (DMA) when dependencies become known.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] The elimination of manual DMA management reduces software complexity, and an associated elimination for hardware cached I/O, reduces the data area expanse that has to be involved with service by specialized computational units such as arithmetic logic units.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] During the 1980s stream processing was explored within dataflow programming.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] An example is the language SISAL (Streams and Iteration in a Single Assignment Language).
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Stream processing is essentially a compromise, driven by a data-centric model that works very well for traditional DSP or GPU-type applications (such as image, video and digital signal processing) but less so for general purpose processing with more randomized data access (such as databases).
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] By sacrificing some flexibility in the model, the implications allow easier, faster and more efficient execution.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Depending on the context, processor design may be tuned for maximum efficiency or a trade-off for flexibility.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] For each record we can only read from the input, perform operations on it, and write to the output.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] It is permissible to have multiple inputs and multiple outputs, but never a piece of memory that is both readable and writable.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] By way of illustration, the following code fragments demonstrate detection of patterns within event streams.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] The first is an example of processing a data stream using a continuous SQL query (a query that executes forever processing arriving data based on timestamps and window duration).
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] This code fragment illustrates a JOIN of two data streams, one for stock orders, and one for the resulting stock trades.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] The query outputs a stream of all Orders matched by a Trade within one second of the Order being placed.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] The output stream is sorted by timestamp, in this case, the timestamp from the Orders stream.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Another sample code fragment detects weddings among a flow of external "events" such as church bells ringing, the appearance of a man in a tuxedo or morning suit, a woman in a flowing white gown and rice flying through the air.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] A "complex" or "composite" event is what one infers from the individual simple events: a wedding is happening.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Basic computers started from a sequential execution paradigm.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Traditional CPUs are SISD based, which means they conceptually perform only one operation at a time.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] As the computing needs of the world evolved, the amount of data to be managed increased very quickly.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] It was obvious that the sequential programming model could not cope with the increased need for processing power.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Various efforts have been spent on finding alternative ways to perform massive amounts of computations but the only solution was to exploit some level of parallel execution.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] The result of those efforts was SIMD, a programming paradigm which allowed applying one instruction to multiple instances of (different) data.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Most of the time, SIMD was being used in a SWAR environment.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] By using more complicated structures, one could also have MIMD parallelism.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Although those two paradigms were efficient, real-world implementations were plagued with limitations from memory alignment problems to synchronization issues and limited parallelism.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Only few SIMD processors survived as stand-alone components; most were embedded in standard CPUs.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Consider a simple program adding up two arrays containing 100 4-component vectors (i.e.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] This is the sequential paradigm that is most familiar.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Variations do exist (such as inner loops, structures and such), but they ultimately boil down to that construct.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] It assumes the instruction `vector_sum` works.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Although this is what happens with instruction intrinsics, much information is actually not taken into account here such as the number of vector components and their data format.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] You can see however, this method reduces the number of decoded instructions from *numElements * componentsPerElement* to *numElements*.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] The number of jump instructions is also decreased, as the loop is run fewer times.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] These gains result from the parallel execution of the four mathematical operations.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] What happened however is that the packed SIMD register holds a certain amount of data so it's not possible to get more parallelism.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] The speed up is somewhat limited by the assumption we made of performing four parallel operations (please note this is common for both AltiVec and SSE).
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] In this paradigm, the whole dataset is defined, rather than each component block being defined separately.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Describing the set of data is assumed to be in the first two rows.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] After that, the result is inferred from the sources and kernel.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] For simplicity, there's a 1:1 mapping between input and output data but this does not need to be.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Applied kernels can also be much more complex.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] An implementation of this paradigm can "unroll" a loop internally.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] This allows throughput to scale with chip complexity, easily utilizing hundreds of ALUs.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] The elimination of complex data patterns makes much of this extra power available.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] While stream processing is a branch of SIMD/MIMD processing, they must not be confused.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Although SIMD implementations can often work in a "streaming" manner, their performance is not comparable: the model envisions a very different usage pattern which allows far greater performance by itself.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] It has been noted that when applied on generic processors such as standard CPU, only a 1.5x speedup can be reached.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] By contrast, ad-hoc stream processors easily reach over 10x performance, mainly attributed to the more efficient memory access and higher levels of parallel processing.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Although there are various degrees of flexibility allowed by the model, stream processors usually impose some limitations on the kernel or stream size.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] For example, consumer hardware often lacks the ability to perform high-precision math, lacks complex indirection chains or presents lower limits on the number of instructions which can be executed.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Stanford University stream processing projects included the Stanford Real-Time Programmable Shading Project started in 1999.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] A prototype called Imagine was developed in 2002.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] A project called Merrimac ran until about 2004.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] AT&T also researched stream-enhanced processors as graphics processing units rapidly evolved in both speed and functionality.[1] Since these early days, dozens of stream processing languages have been developed, as well as specialized hardware.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] The most immediate challenge in the realm of parallel processing does not lie as much in the type of hardware architecture used, but in how easy it will be to program the system in question in a real-world environment with acceptable performance.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Machines like Imagine use a straightforward single-threaded model with automated dependencies, memory allocation and DMA scheduling.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] This in itself is a result of the research at MIT and Stanford in finding an optimal *layering of tasks* between programmer, tools and hardware.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Programmers beat tools in mapping algorithms to parallel hardware, and tools beat programmers in figuring out smartest memory allocation schemes, etc.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Of particular concern are MIMD designs such as Cell, for which the programmer needs to deal with application partitioning across multiple cores and deal with process synchronization and load balancing.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] A drawback of SIMD programming was the issue of array-of-structures (AoS) and structure-of-arrays (SoA).
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] When multiple of these structures exist in memory they are placed end to end creating an arrays in an *array of structures* (AoS) topology.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] This means that should some algorithm be applied to the location of each particle in turn it must skip over memory locations containing the other attributes.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] If these attributes are not needed this results in wasteful usage of the CPU cache.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Additionally, a SIMD instruction will typically expect the data it will operate on to be contiguous in memory, the elements may also need to be aligned.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] By moving the memory location of the data out of the structure data can be better organised for efficient access in a stream and for SIMD instructions to operate one.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] A *structure of arrays* (SoA), as shown below, can allow this.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Instead of holding the data in the structure, it holds only pointers (memory locations) for the data.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Shortcomings are that if multiple attributes to of an object are to be operated on they might now be distant in memory and so result in a cache miss.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] The aligning and any needed padding lead to increased memory usage.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Overall, memory management may be more complicated if structures are added and removed for example.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] For stream processors, the usage of structures is encouraged.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] From an application point of view, all the attributes can be defined with some flexibility.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Taking GPUs as reference, there is a set of attributes (at least 16) available.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] For each attribute, the application can state the number of components and the format of the components (but only primitive data types are supported for now).
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] The various attributes are then attached to a memory block, possibly defining a *stride* between 'consecutive' elements of the same attributes, effectively allowing interleaved data.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] When the GPU begins the stream processing, it will *gather* all the various attributes in a single set of parameters (usually this looks like a structure or a "magic global variable"), performs the operations and *scatters* the results to some memory area for later processing (or retrieving).
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] More modern stream processing frameworks provide a FIFO like interface to structure data as a literal stream.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] This abstraction provides a means to specify data dependencies implicitly while enabling the runtime/hardware to take full advantage of that knowledge for efficient computation.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] One of the simplest and most efficient stream processing modalities to date for C++, is RaftLib, which enables linking independent compute kernels together as a data flow graph using C++ stream operators.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Apart from specifying streaming applications in high-level languages, models of computation (MoCs) also have been widely used as dataflow models and process-based models.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Historically, CPUs began implementing various tiers of memory access optimizations because of the ever-increasing performance when compared to relatively slow growing external memory bandwidth.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] As this gap widened, big amounts of die area were dedicated to hiding memory latencies.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Since fetching information and opcodes to those few ALUs is expensive, very little die area is dedicated to actual mathematical machinery (as a rough estimation, consider it to be less than 10%).
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] A similar architecture exists on stream processors but thanks to the new programming model, the amount of transistors dedicated to management is actually very little.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Beginning from a whole system point of view, stream processors usually exist in a controlled environment.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] GPUs do exist on an add-in board (this seems to also apply to Imagine).
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] CPUs continue do the job of managing system resources, running applications, and such.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] The stream processor is usually equipped with a fast, efficient, proprietary memory bus (crossbar switches are now common, multi-buses have been employed in the past).
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] The exact amount of memory lanes is dependent on the market range.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] As this is written, there are still 64-bit wide interconnections around (entry-level).
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Most mid-range models use a fast 128-bit crossbar switch matrix (4 or 2 segments), while high-end models deploy huge amounts of memory (actually up to 512 MB) with a slightly slower crossbar that is 256 bits wide.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] By contrast, standard processors from Intel Pentium to some Athlon 64 have only a single 64-bit wide data bus.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Memory access patterns are much more predictable.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] While arrays do exist, their dimension is fixed at kernel invocation.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] The thing which most closely matches a multiple pointer indirection is an *indirection chain*, which is however guaranteed to finally read or write from a specific memory area (inside a stream).
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Because of the SIMD nature of the stream processor's execution units (ALUs clusters), read/write operations are expected to happen in bulk, so memories are optimized for high bandwidth rather than low latency (this is a difference from Rambus and DDR SDRAM, for example).
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] This also allows for efficient memory bus negotiations.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Most (90%) of a stream processor's work is done on-chip, requiring only 1% of the global data to be stored to memory.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] This is where knowing the kernel temporaries and dependencies pays.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Internally, a stream processor features some clever communication and management circuits but what's interesting is the *Stream Register File* (SRF).
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] This is conceptually a large cache in which stream data is stored to be transferred to external memory in bulks.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] As a cache-like software-controlled structure to the various ALUs, the SRF is shared between all the various ALU clusters.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] The key concept and innovation here done with Stanford's Imagine chip is that the compiler is able to automate and allocate memory in an optimal way, fully transparent to the programmer.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] The dependencies between kernel functions and data is known through the programming model which enables the compiler to perform flow analysis and optimally pack the SRFs.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Commonly, this cache and DMA management can take up the majority of a project's schedule, something the stream processor (or at least Imagine) totally automates.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Tests done at Stanford showed that the compiler did an as well or better job at scheduling memory than if you hand tuned the thing with much effort.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] There is proof; there can be a lot of clusters because inter-cluster communication is assumed to be rare.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Internally however, each cluster can efficiently exploit a much lower amount of ALUs because intra-cluster communication is common and thus needs to be highly efficient.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] To keep those ALUs fetched with data, each ALU is equipped with local register files (LRFs), which are basically its usable registers.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] This three-tiered data access pattern, makes it easy to keep temporary data away from slow memories, thus making the silicon implementation highly efficient and power-saving.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Although an order of magnitude speedup can be reasonably expected (even from mainstream GPUs when computing in a streaming manner), not all applications benefit from this.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Communication latencies are actually the biggest problem.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Although PCI Express improved this with full-duplex communications, getting a GPU (and possibly a generic stream processor) to work will possibly take long amounts of time.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] This means it's usually counter-productive to use them for small datasets.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Because changing the kernel is a rather expensive operation the stream architecture also incurs penalties for small streams, a behaviour referred to as the *short stream effect*.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Pipelining is a very widespread and heavily used practice on stream processors, with GPUs featuring pipelines exceeding 200 stages.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] The cost for switching settings is dependent on the setting being modified but it is now considered to always be expensive.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] To avoid those problems at various levels of the pipeline, many techniques have been deployed such as "über shaders" and "texture atlases".
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Those techniques are game-oriented because of the nature of GPUs, but the concepts are interesting for generic stream processing as well.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Most programming languages for stream processors start with Java, C or C++ and add extensions which provide specific instructions to allow application developers to tag kernels and/or streams.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] This also applies to most shading languages, which can be considered stream programming languages to a certain degree.
[src:vector-processor/stream-processing] Commercial implementations are either general purpose or tied to specific hardware by a vendor.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] A **supercomputer** is a type of computer with a high level of performance as compared to a general-purpose computer.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] They have been essential in the field of cryptanalysis.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The performance of a supercomputer is commonly measured in floating-point operations per second (FLOPS) instead of million instructions per second (MIPS).
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Since 2022, exascale supercomputers have existed which can perform over 1018 FLOPS.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] For comparison, a desktop computer has performance in the range of hundreds of gigaFLOPS (1011) to tens of teraFLOPS (1013).
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Since November 2017, all of the world's fastest 500 supercomputers run on Linux-based operating systems.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Additional research is being conducted in the United States, the European Union, Taiwan, Japan, and China to build faster, more powerful and technologically superior exascale supercomputers.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Supercomputers were introduced in the 1960s, and for several decades the fastest was made by Seymour Cray at Control Data Corporation (CDC), Cray Research and subsequent companies bearing his name or monogram.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The first such machines were highly tuned conventional designs that ran quicker than their more general-purpose contemporaries.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Through the decade, increasing amounts of parallelism were added, with one to four processors being typical.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] In the 1970s, vector processors operating on large arrays of data came to dominate.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] A notable example is the highly successful Cray-1 of 1976.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Vector computers remained the dominant design into the 1990s.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] From then until today, massively parallel supercomputers with tens of thousands of off-the-shelf processors became the norm.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The U.S. has long been a leader in the supercomputer field, initially through Cray's nearly uninterrupted dominance, and later through a variety of technology companies.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Japan made significant advancements in the field during the 1980s and 1990s, while China has become increasingly active in supercomputing in recent years.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] As of November 2024, Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory's El Capitan is the world's fastest supercomputer.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The US has five of the top 10; Italy two, Japan, Finland, Switzerland have one each.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] In 1960, UNIVAC built the Livermore Atomic Research Computer (LARC), today considered among the first supercomputers, for the US Navy Research and Development Center.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] It still used high-speed drum memory, rather than the newly emerging disk drive technology.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Also, among the first supercomputers was the IBM 7030 Stretch.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The IBM 7030 was built by IBM for the Los Alamos National Laboratory, which then in 1955 had requested a computer 100 times faster than any existing computer.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The IBM 7030 used transistors, magnetic core memory, pipelined instructions, prefetched data through a memory controller and included pioneering random access disk drives.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The IBM 7030 was completed in 1961 and despite not meeting the challenge of a hundredfold increase in performance, it was purchased by the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Customers in England and France also bought the computer, and it became the basis for the IBM 7950 Harvest, a supercomputer built for cryptanalysis.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The third pioneering supercomputer project in the early 1960s was the Atlas at the University of Manchester, built by a team led by Tom Kilburn.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] He designed the Atlas to have memory space for up to a million words of 48 bits, but because magnetic storage with such a capacity was unaffordable, the actual core memory of the Atlas was only 16,000 words, with a drum providing memory for a further 96,000 words.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The Atlas Supervisor swapped data in the form of pages between the magnetic core and the drum.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The Atlas operating system also introduced time-sharing to supercomputing, so that more than one program could be executed on the supercomputer at any one time.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Atlas was a joint venture between Ferranti and Manchester University and was designed to operate at processing speeds approaching one microsecond per instruction, about one million instructions per second.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The CDC 6600, designed by Seymour Cray, was finished in 1964 and marked the transition from germanium to silicon transistors.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Silicon transistors could run more quickly and the overheating problem was solved by introducing refrigeration to the supercomputer design.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Thus, the CDC6600 became the fastest computer in the world.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Given that the 6600 outperformed all the other contemporary computers by about 10 times, it was dubbed a *supercomputer* and defined the supercomputing market, when one hundred computers were sold at $8 million each.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Cray left CDC in 1972 to form his own company, Cray Research.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Four years after leaving CDC, Cray delivered the 80 MHz Cray-1 in 1976, which became one of the most successful supercomputers in history.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] It had eight central processing units (CPUs), liquid cooling and the electronics coolant liquid Fluorinert was pumped through the supercomputer architecture.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] It reached 1.9 gigaFLOPS, making it the first supercomputer to break the gigaflop barrier.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The only computer to seriously challenge the Cray-1's performance in the 1970s was the ILLIAC IV.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] This machine was the first realized example of a true massively parallel computer, in which many processors worked together to solve different parts of a single larger problem.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] In contrast with the vector systems, which were designed to run a single stream of data as quickly as possible, in this concept, the computer instead feeds separate parts of the data to entirely different processors and then recombines the results.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The ILLIAC's design was finalized in 1966 with 256 processors and offer speed up to 1 GFLOPS, compared to the 1970s Cray-1's peak of 250 MFLOPS.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] However, development problems led to only 64 processors being built, and the system could never operate more quickly than about 200 MFLOPS while being much larger and more complex than the Cray.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Another problem was that writing software for the system was difficult, and getting peak performance from it was a matter of serious effort.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] But the partial success of the ILLIAC IV was widely seen as pointing the way to the future of supercomputing.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Cray argued against this, famously quipping that "If you were plowing a field, which would you rather use?
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Two strong oxen or 1024 chickens?" But by the early 1980s, several teams were working on parallel designs with thousands of processors, notably the Connection Machine (CM) that developed from research at MIT.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The CM-1 used as many as 65,536 simplified custom microprocessors connected together in a network to share data.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Several updated versions followed; the CM-5 supercomputer is a massively parallel processing computer capable of many billions of arithmetic operations per second.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] In 1982, Osaka University's LINKS-1 Computer Graphics System used a massively parallel processing architecture, with 514 microprocessors, including 257 Zilog Z8001 control processors and 257 iAPX 86/20 floating-point processors.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] It was mainly used for rendering realistic 3D computer graphics.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Fujitsu's VPP500 from 1992 is unusual since, to achieve higher speeds, its processors used GaAs, a material normally reserved for microwave applications due to its toxicity.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Fujitsu's Numerical Wind Tunnel supercomputer used 166 vector processors to gain the top spot in 1994 with a peak speed of 1.7 gigaFLOPS (GFLOPS) per processor.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The Hitachi SR2201 obtained a peak performance of 600 GFLOPS in 1996 by using 2048 processors connected via a fast three-dimensional crossbar network.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The Intel Paragon could have 1000 to 4000 Intel i860 processors in various configurations and was ranked the fastest in the world in 1993.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The Paragon was a MIMD machine which connected processors via a high speed two-dimensional mesh, allowing processes to execute on separate nodes, communicating via the Message Passing Interface.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Software development remained a problem, but the CM series sparked off considerable research into this issue.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Similar designs using custom hardware were made by many companies, including the Evans & Sutherland ES-1, MasPar, nCUBE, Intel iPSC and the Goodyear MPP.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] But by the mid-1990s, general-purpose CPU performance had improved so much in that a supercomputer could be built using them as the individual processing units, instead of using custom chips.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] By the turn of the 21st century, designs featuring tens of thousands of commodity CPUs were the norm, with later machines adding graphic units to the mix.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] In 1998, David Bader developed the first Linux supercomputer using commodity parts.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] While at the University of New Mexico, Bader sought to build a supercomputer running Linux using consumer off-the-shelf parts and a high-speed low-latency interconnection network.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The prototype utilized an Alta Technologies "AltaCluster" of eight dual, 333 MHz, Intel Pentium II computers running a modified Linux kernel.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Bader ported a significant amount of software to provide Linux support for necessary components as well as code from members of the National Computational Science Alliance (NCSA) to ensure interoperability, as none of it had been run on Linux previously.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Using the successful prototype design, he led the development of "RoadRunner," the first Linux supercomputer for open use by the national science and engineering community via the National Science Foundation's National Technology Grid.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] RoadRunner was put into production use in April 1999.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] At the time of its deployment, it was considered one of the 100 fastest supercomputers in the world.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Though Linux-based clusters using consumer-grade parts, such as Beowulf, existed prior to the development of Bader's prototype and RoadRunner, they lacked the scalability, bandwidth, and parallel computing capabilities to be considered "true" supercomputers.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Systems with a massive number of processors generally take one of two paths.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] In the grid computing approach, the processing power of many computers, organized as distributed, diverse administrative domains, is opportunistically used whenever a computer is available.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] In another approach, many processors are used in proximity to each other, e.g. in a computer cluster.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] In such a centralized massively parallel system the speed and flexibility of the *interconnect* becomes very important and modern supercomputers have used various approaches ranging from enhanced Infiniband systems to three-dimensional torus interconnects.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The use of multi-core processors combined with centralization is an emerging direction, e.g. as in the Cyclops64 system.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] As the price, performance and energy efficiency of general-purpose graphics processing units (GPGPUs) have improved, a number of petaFLOPS supercomputers such as Tianhe-I and Nebulae have started to rely on them.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] However, GPUs are gaining ground, and in 2012 the Jaguar supercomputer was transformed into Titan by retrofitting CPUs with GPUs.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] High-performance computers have an expected life cycle of about three years before requiring an upgrade.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The Gyoukou supercomputer is unique in that it uses both a massively parallel design and liquid immersion cooling.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] A number of special-purpose systems have been designed, dedicated to a single problem.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] This allows the use of specially programmed FPGA chips or even custom ASICs, allowing better price/performance ratios by sacrificing generality.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Examples of special-purpose supercomputers include Belle, Deep Blue, and Hydra for playing chess, Gravity Pipe for astrophysics, MDGRAPE-3 for protein structure prediction and molecular dynamics, and Deep Crack for breaking the DES cipher.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Throughout the decades, the management of heat density has remained a key issue for most centralized supercomputers.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The large amount of heat generated by a system may also have other effects, e.g. reducing the lifetime of other system components.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] There have been diverse approaches to heat management, from pumping Fluorinert through the system, to a hybrid liquid-air cooling system or air cooling with normal air conditioning temperatures.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] A typical supercomputer consumes large amounts of electrical power, almost all of which is converted into heat, requiring cooling.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] For example, Tianhe-1A consumes 4.04 megawatts (MW) of electricity.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The cost to power and cool the system can be significant, e.g.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] 4 MW at $0.10/kWh is $400 an hour or about $3.5 million per year.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Heat management is a major issue in complex electronic devices and affects powerful computer systems in various ways.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The thermal design power and CPU power dissipation issues in supercomputing surpass those of traditional computer cooling technologies.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The supercomputing awards for green computing reflect this issue.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The packing of thousands of processors together inevitably generates significant amounts of heat density that need to be dealt with.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The Cray-2 was liquid cooled, and used a Fluorinert "cooling waterfall" which was forced through the modules under pressure.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] However, the submerged liquid cooling approach was not practical for the multi-cabinet systems based on off-the-shelf processors, and in System X a special cooling system that combined air conditioning with liquid cooling was developed in conjunction with the Liebert company.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] In the Blue Gene system, IBM deliberately used low power processors to deal with heat density.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The IBM Power 775, released in 2011, has closely packed elements that require water cooling.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The IBM Aquasar system uses hot water cooling to achieve energy efficiency, the water being used to heat buildings as well.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The energy efficiency of computer systems is generally measured in terms of "FLOPS per watt".
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] In 2008, Roadrunner by IBM operated at 376 MFLOPS/W.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] In November 2010, the Blue Gene/Q reached 1684 MFLOPS/W and in June 2011 the top two spots on the Green 500 list were occupied by Blue Gene machines in New York (one achieving 2097 MFLOPS/W) with the DEGIMA cluster in Nagasaki placing third with 1375 MFLOPS/W.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Because copper wires can transfer energy into a supercomputer with much higher power densities than forced air or circulating refrigerants can remove waste heat, the ability of the cooling systems to remove waste heat is a limiting factor.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] As of 2015, many existing supercomputers have more infrastructure capacity than the actual peak demand of the machine – designers generally conservatively design the power and cooling infrastructure to handle more than the theoretical peak electrical power consumed by the supercomputer.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Since the end of the 20th century, supercomputer operating systems have undergone major transformations, based on the changes in supercomputer architecture.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] While early operating systems were custom tailored to each supercomputer to gain speed, the trend has been to move away from in-house operating systems to the adaptation of generic software such as Linux.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The parallel architectures of supercomputers often dictate the use of special programming techniques to exploit their speed.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Software tools for distributed processing include standard APIs such as MPI and PVM, VTL, and open source software such as Beowulf.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] In the most common scenario, environments such as PVM and MPI for loosely connected clusters and OpenMP for tightly coordinated shared memory machines are used.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Significant effort is required to optimize an algorithm for the interconnect characteristics of the machine it will be run on; the aim is to prevent any of the CPUs from wasting time waiting on data from other nodes.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] GPGPUs have hundreds of processor cores and are programmed using programming models such as CUDA or OpenCL.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Moreover, it is quite difficult to debug and test parallel programs.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Special techniques need to be used for testing and debugging such applications.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Opportunistic supercomputing is a form of networked grid computing whereby a "super virtual computer" of many loosely coupled volunteer computing machines performs very large computing tasks.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Grid computing has been applied to a number of large-scale embarrassingly parallel problems that require supercomputing performance scales.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] However, basic grid and cloud computing approaches that rely on volunteer computing cannot handle traditional supercomputing tasks such as fluid dynamic simulations.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The fastest grid computing system is the volunteer computing project Folding@home (F@h).
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] As of April 2020, F@h reported 2.5 exaFLOPS of x86 processing power.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Of this, over 100 PFLOPS are contributed by clients running on various GPUs, and the rest from various CPU systems.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The Berkeley Open Infrastructure for Network Computing (BOINC) platform hosts a number of volunteer computing projects.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] As of February 2017, BOINC recorded a processing power of over 166 petaFLOPS through over 762 thousand active Computers (Hosts) on the network.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] As of October 2016, Great Internet Mersenne Prime Search's (GIMPS) distributed Mersenne Prime search achieved about 0.313 PFLOPS through over 1.3 million computers.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The PrimeNet server has supported GIMPS's grid computing approach, one of the earliest volunteer computing projects, since 1997.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Quasi-opportunistic supercomputing is a form of distributed computing whereby the "super virtual computer" of many networked geographically disperse computers performs computing tasks that demand huge processing power.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Cloud computing with its recent and rapid expansions and development have grabbed the attention of high-performance computing (HPC) users and developers in recent years.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Cloud computing attempts to provide HPC-as-a-service exactly like other forms of services available in the cloud such as software as a service, platform as a service, and infrastructure as a service.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] HPC users may benefit from the cloud in different angles such as scalability, resources being on-demand, fast, and inexpensive.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] On the other hand, moving HPC applications have a set of challenges too.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Good examples of such challenges are virtualization overhead in the cloud, multi-tenancy of resources, and network latency issues.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Much research is currently being done to overcome these challenges and make HPC in the cloud a more realistic possibility.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] In 2016, Penguin Computing, Parallel Works, R-HPC, Amazon Web Services, Univa, Silicon Graphics International, Rescale, Sabalcore, and Gomput started to offer HPC cloud computing.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The Penguin On Demand (POD) cloud is a bare-metal compute model to execute code, but each user is given virtualized login node.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] POD computing nodes are connected via non-virtualized 10 Gbit/s Ethernet or QDR InfiniBand networks.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] User connectivity to the POD data center ranges from 50 Mbit/s to 1 Gbit/s.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Citing Amazon's EC2 Elastic Compute Cloud, Penguin Computing argues that virtualization of compute nodes is not suitable for HPC.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Penguin Computing has also criticized that HPC clouds may have allocated computing nodes to customers that are far apart, causing latency that impairs performance for some HPC applications.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Supercomputers generally aim for the maximum in capability computing rather than capacity computing.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Capability computing is typically thought of as using the maximum computing power to solve a single large problem in the shortest amount of time.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Often a capability system is able to solve a problem of a size or complexity that no other computer can, e.g. a very complex weather simulation application.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Capacity computing, in contrast, is typically thought of as using efficient cost-effective computing power to solve a few somewhat large problems or many small problems.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Architectures that lend themselves to supporting many users for routine everyday tasks may have a lot of capacity but are not typically considered supercomputers, given that they do not solve a single very complex problem.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] In general, the speed of supercomputers is measured and benchmarked in FLOPS (floating-point operations per second), and not in terms of MIPS (million instructions per second), as is the case with general-purpose computers.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Exascale is computing performance in the exaFLOPS (EFLOPS) range.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] An EFLOPS is one quintillion (1018) FLOPS (one million TFLOPS).
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] However, the performance of a supercomputer can be severely impacted by fluctuation brought on by elements like system load, network traffic, and concurrent processes, as mentioned by Brehm and Bruhwiler (2015).
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] No single number can reflect the overall performance of a computer system, yet the goal of the Linpack benchmark is to approximate how fast the computer solves numerical problems and it is widely used in the industry.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The LINPACK benchmark typically performs LU decomposition of a large matrix.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Since 1993, the fastest supercomputers have been ranked on the TOP500 list according to their LINPACK benchmark results.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The list does not claim to be unbiased or definitive, but it is a widely cited current definition of the "fastest" supercomputer available at any given time.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] This is a list of the computers which appeared at the top of the TOP500 list since June 1993, and the "Peak speed" is given as the "Rmax" rating.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] In 2018, Lenovo became the world's largest provider for the TOP500 supercomputers with 117 units produced.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The application of supercomputers has evolved significantly since the 1970s, expanding across numerous fields of scientific and governmental research.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] In the 1970s, the Cray-1 supercomputer was instrumental in early weather forecasting and aerodynamic research.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The scope broadened in the 1980s with machines like the CDC Cyber facilitating probabilistic analyses and modeling radiation shielding.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The 1990s saw supercomputers, such as the EFF DES cracker, applied to brute-force tasks like code-breaking.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Moving into the 2000s, supercomputers became crucial for national security applications; the ASCI Q was used to conduct 3D nuclear test simulations, satisfying the requirements of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty without physical testing.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The 2010s brought advancements in molecular dynamics simulations, exemplified by the use of the Tianhe-1A.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The trend has continued into the 2020s, with supercomputers providing powerful tools for research into outbreak prevention and electrochemical reactions.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Beyond these specific decades, supercomputers have been pivotal in major scientific endeavors.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] For instance, the IBM Blue Gene/P was used to simulate a network of artificial neurons equivalent to one percent of a human cerebral cortex (1.6 billion neurons and 9 trillion connections), and the same team later simulated the entirety of a rat's brain.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Modern applications are diverse and critical.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Weather forecasting relies heavily on supercomputing power, with the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration utilizing these systems to process vast quantities of observational data to enhance forecast accuracy.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The United States also employs supercomputers through the Advanced Simulation and Computing Program to maintain and simulate its nuclear stockpile.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The field has its challenges, as highlighted by IBM's abandonment of the ambitious Blue Waters petascale project in 2011.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Despite such setbacks, the utility of supercomputers continues to grow.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] A recent example of their critical role occurred in early 2020, when supercomputers were rapidly deployed to run extensive simulations using numerous paralleled CPUs to identify compounds with the potential to stop the spread of COVID-19.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] In the 2010s, China, the United States, the European Union, and others competed to be the first to create a 1 exaFLOP (1018 or one quintillion FLOPS) supercomputer.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] DeBenedictis of Sandia National Laboratories has theorized that a zettaFLOPS (1021 or one sextillion FLOPS) computer is required to accomplish full weather modeling, which could cover a two-week time span accurately.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Such systems might be built around 2030.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Many Monte Carlo simulations use the same algorithm to process a randomly generated data set; particularly, integro-differential equations describing physical transport processes, the random paths, collisions, and energy and momentum depositions of neutrons, photons, ions, electrons, etc.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The next step for microprocessors may be into the third dimension; and specializing to Monte Carlo, the many layers could be identical, simplifying the design and manufacture process.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The cost of operating high performance supercomputers has risen, mainly due to increasing power consumption.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] In the mid-1990s a top 10 supercomputer required in the range of 100 kilowatts, in 2010 the top 10 supercomputers required between 1 and 2 megawatts.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] A 2010 study commissioned by DARPA identified power consumption as the most pervasive challenge in achieving Exascale computing.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] At the time a megawatt per year in energy consumption cost about 1 million dollars.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Supercomputing facilities were constructed to efficiently remove the increasing amount of heat produced by modern multi-core central processing units.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Based on the energy consumption of the Green 500 list of supercomputers between 2007 and 2011, a supercomputer with 1 exaFLOPS in 2011 would have required nearly 500 megawatts.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Operating systems were developed for existing hardware to conserve energy whenever possible.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] CPU cores not in use during the execution of a parallelized application were put into low-power states, producing energy savings for some supercomputing applications.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The increasing cost of operating supercomputers has been a driving factor in a trend toward bundling of resources through a distributed supercomputer infrastructure.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] National supercomputing centers first emerged in the US, followed by Germany and Japan.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The European Union launched the Partnership for Advanced Computing in Europe (PRACE) with the aim of creating a persistent pan-European supercomputer infrastructure with services to support scientists across the European Union in porting, scaling and optimizing supercomputing applications.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Iceland built the world's first zero-emission supercomputer.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Located at the Thor Data Center in Reykjavík, Iceland, this supercomputer relies on completely renewable sources for its power rather than fossil fuels.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] The colder climate also reduces the need for active cooling, making it one of the greenest facilities in the world of computers.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Funding supercomputer hardware also became increasingly difficult.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] In the mid-1990s a top 10 supercomputer cost about 10 million euros, while in 2010 the top 10 supercomputers required an investment of between 40 and 50 million euros.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] In the 2000s national governments put in place different strategies to fund supercomputers.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] In the UK the national government funded supercomputers entirely and high performance computing was put under the control of a national funding agency.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Germany developed a mixed funding model, pooling local state funding and federal funding.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] Examples of supercomputers in fiction include HAL 9000, Multivac, The Machine Stops, GLaDOS, SHODAN, The Evitable Conflict, Vulcan's Hammer, Colossus, WOPR, AM, and Deep Thought.
[src:vector-processor/supercomputer] A supercomputer from Thinking Machines was mentioned as the supercomputer used to sequence the DNA extracted from preserved parasites in the Jurassic Park series.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] In computing, a **vector processor** is a central processing unit (CPU) that implements an instruction set where its instructions are designed to operate efficiently and architecturally sequentially on large one-dimensional arrays of data called *vectors*.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] When integrated as a hardware component the vector processor is often called a **vector processing unit** (VPU).
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] This is in contrast to scalar processors, whose instructions operate on single data items only, and in contrast to some of those same scalar processors having additional single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) or SIMD within a register (SWAR) Arithmetic Units.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Vector processors can greatly improve performance on certain workloads, notably numerical simulation, compression and similar tasks.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Vector processing techniques also operate in video-game console hardware and in graphics accelerators but these are invariably Single instruction, multiple threads (SIMT) and occasionally Single instruction, multiple data (SIMD).
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Vector machines appeared in the early 1970s and dominated supercomputer design through the 1970s into the 1990s, notably the various Cray platforms.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The rapid fall in the price-to-performance ratio of conventional microprocessor designs led to a decline in vector supercomputers during the 1990s.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Array processing development began in the early 1960s at the Westinghouse Electric Corporation in their *Solomon* project.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Solomon's goal was to dramatically increase math performance by using a large number of simple coprocessors under the control of a single master Central processing unit (CPU).
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The CPU fed a single common instruction to all of the arithmetic logic units (ALUs), one per cycle, but with a different data point for each one to work on.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] This allowed the Solomon machine to apply a single algorithm to a large data set, fed in the form of an array, leading it to be cited as an example Array processor in Flynn's taxonomy.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] In 1962, Westinghouse cancelled the project, but the effort was restarted by the University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign as the ILLIAC IV.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Their version of the design originally called for a 1 GFLOPS machine with 256 ALUs, but, when it was finally delivered in 1972, it had only 64 ALUs and could reach only 100 to 150 MFLOPS.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Nevertheless, it showed that the basic concept was sound, and, when used on data-intensive applications, such as computational fluid dynamics, the ILLIAC was the fastest machine in the world.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The ILLIAC approach of using separate ALUs for each data element is not common to later designs, and is often referred to under a separate category of massively parallel computing: around 1972 Flynn categorized this type of processing as an early form of single instruction, multiple threads (SIMT).
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] A computer for operations with functions was presented and developed by Kartsev in 1967.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The first vector supercomputers are the Control Data Corporation STAR-100 and Texas Instruments Advanced Scientific Computer (ASC), which were introduced in 1974 and 1972, respectively.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The basic ASC (i.e., "one pipe") ALU used a pipeline architecture that supported both scalar and vector computations, with peak performance reaching approximately 20 MFLOPS, readily achieved when processing long vectors.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Expanded ALU configurations supported "two pipes" or "four pipes" with a corresponding 2X or 4X performance gain.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Memory bandwidth was sufficient to support these expanded modes.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The STAR-100 was otherwise slower than CDC's own supercomputers like the CDC 7600, but at data-related tasks they could keep up while being much smaller and less expensive.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] However the machine also took considerable time decoding the vector instructions and getting ready to run the process, so it required very specific data sets to work on before it actually sped anything up.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The vector technique was first fully exploited in 1976 by the famous Cray-1.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Instead of leaving the data in memory like the STAR-100 and ASC, the Cray design had eight vector registers, which held sixty-four 64-bit words each.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The vector instructions were applied between registers, which is much faster than talking to main memory.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The Cray design used pipeline parallelism to implement vector instructions rather than multiple ALUs.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] In addition, the design had completely separate pipelines for different instructions, for example, addition/subtraction was implemented in different hardware than multiplication.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] This allowed a batch of vector instructions to be pipelined into each of the ALU subunits, a technique they called *vector chaining*.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The Cray-1 normally had a performance of about 80 MFLOPS, but with up to three chains running it could peak at 240 MFLOPS and averaged around 150 – far faster than any machine of the era.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Control Data Corporation tried to re-enter the high-end market again with its ETA-10 machine, but it sold poorly and they took that as an opportunity to leave the supercomputing field entirely.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] In the early and mid-1980s Japanese companies Fujitsu, Hitachi and NEC introduced register-based vector machines similar to the Cray-1, typically being slightly faster and much smaller: the Fujitsu VP series culminated in the VP2600 holding the world record fastest supercomputer in 1990-1991.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Oregon-based Floating Point Systems (FPS) built add-on array processors for minicomputers, later building their own minisupercomputers.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Throughout, Cray continued to be the performance leader, continually beating the competition with a series of machines that led to the Cray-2, Cray X-MP and Cray Y-MP.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Since then, the supercomputer market has focused much more on massively parallel processing rather than better implementations of vector processors.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] However, recognising the benefits of vector processing, IBM developed Virtual Vector Architecture for use in supercomputers coupling several scalar processors to act as a vector processor.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] IBM also implemented Cray-style Vector processing in the IBM 3090 with an optional vector facility.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Although vector supercomputers resembling the Cray-1 are less popular these days, NEC has continued to make this type of computer up to the present day with their SX series of computers.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Modern graphics processing units (GPUs) include an array of shader pipelines which may be driven by compute kernels, and being usually SIMT are frequently miscategorised as vector processors, the two being very similar categorisation of SIMD in Flynn's 1972 SIMD taxonomy.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] GPUs use a strategy for hiding memory latencies as they run into an extreme form of the memory wall.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Thus although all cores simultaneously execute the exact same instruction in lock-step with each other they do so with completely different data from completely different memory locations.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] This is *significantly* more complex and involved than "Packed SIMD", which is strictly limited to execution of parallel pipelined arithmetic operations only.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Although the exact internal details of today's commercial GPUs are proprietary secrets, the MIAOW team was able to piece together anecdotal information sufficient to implement a subset of the AMDGPU architecture.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Several modern CPU architectures are being designed as vector processors.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The RISC-V vector extension follows similar principles as the early vector processors, and is being implemented in commercial products such as the Andes Technology AX45MPV.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] There are also several open source vector processor architectures being developed, including ForwardCom and Libre-SOC.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] As of 2016 most commodity CPUs implement architectures that feature fixed-length SIMD instructions.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] On first inspection these can be considered a form of vector processing because they operate on multiple (vectorized, explicit length) data sets, and borrow features from vector processors.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] However, by definition, the addition of SIMD cannot, by itself, qualify a processor as an actual *vector processor*, because SIMD is *fixed-length*, and vectors are *variable-length*.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The difference is illustrated below with examples, showing and comparing the three categories: pure SIMD, predicated SIMD, and pure vector processing.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Other CPU designs include some multiple instructions for vector processing on multiple (vectorized) data sets, typically known as MIMD (multiple instruction, multiple data) and realized with VLIW (very long instruction word) and EPIC (explicitly parallel instruction computing).
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The Fujitsu FR-V, for example, combines VLIW features with predication and packed SIMD.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] SIMD instruction sets lack crucial features when compared to vector instruction sets.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The most important of these is that vector processors, inherently by definition and design, have always been designed to work on variable-length vectors, not restricted to power of two, since their inception.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Pure (fixed-width, no predication) SIMD is often mistakenly claimed to be "vector" (because SIMD processes data which happens to be vectors).
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Close analysis and comparison of historic and modern ISAs shows actual vector ISAs to have a way to set the vector length at runtime, and to a non-power-of-two quantity.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] In other words, the number of elements is *not* hard-encoded in the instruction as it is in SIMD ISA.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] This is explained in the "SIMD Considered harmful" article.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] An additional key feature is element-level predicated masking.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] In the Cyber 200 Model the element-level bitmask was itself a Vector stored in memory.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Some Vector processors have Vector mask registers as exemplified by the Cray-1 which, like the Cyber 200, efficiently used one bit per element as a mask.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] However other Vector ISAs such as RISC-V elected to use a register from the main Vector register file.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Predicated SIMD (part of Flynn's taxonomy) is comprehensive individual element-level predicate masks on every element, as is now available in ARM SVE2 and AVX-512, but neither of these Instruction sets has an actual explicit "set vector length" instruction.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Predicated SIMD uses fixed-width SIMD ALUs but allows locally controlled (predicated) activation of units to provide the appearance of variable length vectors.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Examples below help explain these categorical distinctions.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Another key difference: SIMD, because it uses fixed-width batch processing, is *unable by design* to cope with iteration and reduction.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] This is illustrated further with examples, below.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Chaining is a performance technique that allows partial outputs of a vector operation to be used as inputs to a subsequent operation without waiting for the first operation to complete.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The technique was first used by Seymour Cray in the 80 MHz Cray 1 supercomputer in 1976.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Computers are able to manipulate one or more pieces of data at a time, by following machine code with predefined meanings (an instruction set).
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] An instruction for addition may, for example, perform what's essentially "add A to B and put the result in C".
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The data for A, B and C could be—in theory, at least—encoded directly into the instruction.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] However, in efficient implementation things are rarely that simple.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The data is rarely sent in raw form, and is instead "pointed to" by passing in an address to a memory location that holds the data.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Decoding this address and getting the data out of the memory takes some time, during which the CPU traditionally would sit idle waiting for the requested data to show up.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] As CPU speeds have increased, this memory latency has historically become a large impediment to performance; see Random-access memory § Memory wall.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] To reduce the amount of time consumed by these steps, most modern CPUs use a technique known as instruction pipelining in which the instructions pass through several sub-units in turn.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The first sub-unit reads the address and decodes it, the next "fetches" the values at those addresses, and the next does the math itself.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] With pipelining the "trick" is to start decoding the next instruction even before the first has left the CPU, in the fashion of an assembly line, so the address decoder is constantly in use.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Any particular instruction takes the same amount of time to complete, a time known as the *latency*, but the CPU can process an entire batch of operations, in an overlapping fashion, much faster and more efficiently than if it did so one at a time.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Vector processors take this concept one step further.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Instead of pipelining just the instructions, they also pipeline the data itself.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The processor is fed instructions that say not just to add A to B, but to add all of the numbers "from here to here" to all of the numbers "from there to there".
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] This significantly maximises instruction effectiveness.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] To illustrate what a difference this can make, consider the simple task of adding two groups of 10 numbers together.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] In a normal programming language one would write a "loop" that picked up each of the pairs of numbers in turn, and then added them.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Note the complete lack of looping in the instructions, because it is the *hardware* which has performed 10 sequential operations: effectively the loop count is on an explicit *per-instruction* basis.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] There are several savings inherent in this approach.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Another saving is fetching and decoding the instruction itself, which has to be done only one time instead of ten.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The code itself is also smaller, which can lead to more efficient memory use, reduction in L1 instruction cache size, reduction in power consumption.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] With the program size being reduced branch prediction has an easier job.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] With the length (equivalent to SIMD width) not being hard-coded into the instruction, not only is the encoding more compact, it's also "future-proof" and allows even embedded processor designs to consider using vectors purely to gain all the other advantages, rather than go for high performance.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Additionally, in more modern vector processor ISAs, "Fail on First" or "Fault First" has been introduced (see below) which brings even more advantages.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] But more than that, a high performance vector processor may have multiple functional units adding those numbers in parallel.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The checking of dependencies between those numbers is not required as a vector instruction specifies multiple independent operations.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] This simplifies the control logic required, and can further improve performance by avoiding stalls.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The math operations thus completed far faster overall, the limiting factor being the time required to fetch the data from memory.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Not all problems can be attacked with this sort of solution.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Including these types of instructions necessarily adds complexity to the core CPU.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] That complexity typically makes *other* instructions run slower—i.e., whenever it is **not** adding up many numbers in a row.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The more complex instructions also add to the complexity of the decoders, which might slow down the decoding of the more common instructions such as normal adding.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Vector processors were traditionally designed to work best only when there are large amounts of data to be worked on.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] For this reason, these sorts of CPUs were found primarily in supercomputers, as the supercomputers themselves were, in general, found in places such as weather prediction centers and physics labs, where huge amounts of data are "crunched".
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] However, as shown above the *efficiency* of vector ISAs brings other benefits which are compelling even for Embedded use-cases.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The vector pseudocode example above comes with a big assumption that the vector computer can process more than ten numbers in one batch.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] For a greater quantity of numbers in the vector register, it becomes unfeasible for the computer to have a register that large.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] As a result, the vector processor either gains the ability to perform loops itself, or exposes some sort of vector control (status) register to the programmer, usually known as a vector Length.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The self-repeating instructions are found in early vector computers like the STAR-100, where the above action would be described in a single instruction (somewhat like `vadd c, a, b, $10`).
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] They are also found in the x86 architecture as the `REP` prefix.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] However, only very simple calculations can be done effectively in hardware this way without a very large cost increase.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Since all operands have to be in memory for the STAR-100 architecture, the latency caused by access became huge too.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Broadcom included space in all vector operations of the Videocore IV ISA for a `REP` field, but unlike the STAR-100 which uses memory for its repeats, the Videocore IV repeats are on all operations including arithmetic vector operations.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The repeat length can be a small range of power of two or sourced from one of the scalar registers.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The Cray-1 introduced the idea of using processor registers to hold vector data in batches.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The batch lengths (vector length, VL) could be dynamically set with a special instruction, the significance compared to Videocore IV (and, crucially as will be shown below, SIMD as well) being that the repeat length does not have to be part of the instruction encoding.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] This way, significantly more work can be done in each batch; the instruction encoding is much more elegant and compact as well.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The only drawback is that in order to take full advantage of this extra batch processing capacity, the memory load and store speed correspondingly had to increase as well.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] This is sometimes claimed to be a disadvantage of Cray-style vector processors, and the Fujitsu VP series did make this mistake: in reality it is part of achieving high performance throughput, as seen in GPUs, which face exactly the same issue.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Modern SIMD computers claim to improve on early Cray by directly using multiple ALUs, for a higher degree of parallelism compared to only using the normal scalar pipeline.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Modern vector processors (such as the SX-Aurora TSUBASA) combine both, by issuing multiple data to multiple internal pipelined SIMD ALUs, the number issued being dynamically chosen by the vector program at runtime.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Masks can be used to selectively load and store data in memory locations, and use those same masks to selectively disable processing element of SIMD ALUs.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Some processors with SIMD (AVX-512, ARM SVE2) are capable of this kind of selective, per-element ("predicated") processing, and it is these which somewhat deserve the nomenclature "vector processor" or at least deserve the claim of being capable of "vector processing".
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] SIMD processors without per-element predication (MMX, SSE, AltiVec) categorically do not.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Modern GPUs, which have many small compute units each with their own independent SIMD ALUs, use Single Instruction Multiple Threads (SIMT).
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] SIMT units run from a shared single broadcast synchronised Instruction Unit.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The "vector registers" are very wide and the pipelines tend to be long.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The "threading" part of SIMT involves the way data is handled independently on each of the compute units.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The Broadcom Videocore IV is also capable of this hybrid approach: nominally stating that its SIMD QPU Engine supports 16-long FP array operations in its instructions, it actually does them 4 at a time, as (another) form of "threads".
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] This example starts with an algorithm ("IAXPY"), first show it in scalar instructions, then SIMD, then predicated SIMD, and finally vector instructions.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] This incrementally helps illustrate the difference between a traditional vector processor and a modern SIMD one.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] In each iteration, every element of y has an element of x multiplied by a and added to it.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The program is expressed in scalar linear form for readability.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The STAR-like code remains concise, but because the STAR-100's vectorisation was by design based around memory accesses, an extra slot of memory is now required to process the information.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Two times the latency is also needed due to the extra requirement of memory access.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] A modern packed SIMD architecture, known by many names (listed in Flynn's taxonomy), can do most of the operation in batches.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The code is mostly similar to the scalar version.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] It is assumed that both x and y are properly aligned here (only start on a multiple of 16) and that n is a multiple of 4, as otherwise some setup code would be needed to calculate a mask or to run a scalar version.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] It can also be assumed, for simplicity, that the SIMD instructions have an option to automatically repeat scalar operands, like ARM NEON can.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The time taken would be basically the same as a vector implementation of `y = mx + c` described above.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Note that both x and y pointers are incremented by 16, because that is how long (in bytes) four 32-bit integers are.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The decision was made that the algorithm *shall* only cope with 4-wide SIMD, therefore the constant is hard-coded into the program.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Unfortunately for SIMD, the clue was in the assumption above, "that n is a multiple of 4" as well as "aligned access", which, clearly, is a limited specialist use-case.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Realistically, for general-purpose loops such as in portable libraries, where n cannot be limited in this way, the overhead of setup and cleanup for SIMD in order to cope with non-multiples of the SIMD width, can far exceed the instruction count inside the loop itself.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Eight-wide SIMD requires repeating the inner loop algorithm first with four-wide SIMD elements, then two-wide SIMD, then one (scalar), with a test and branch in between each one, in order to cover the first and last remaining SIMD elements (0 <= n <= 7).
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] This more than *triples* the size of the code, in fact in extreme cases it results in an *order of magnitude* increase in instruction count!
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] This can easily be demonstrated by compiling the iaxpy example for AVX-512, using the options `"-O3 -march=knl"` to gcc.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Over time as the ISA evolves to keep increasing performance, it results in ISA Architects adding 2-wide SIMD, then 4-wide SIMD, then 8-wide and upwards.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] It can therefore be seen why AVX-512 exists in x86.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Without predication, the wider the SIMD width the worse the problems get, leading to massive opcode proliferation, degraded performance, extra power consumption and unnecessary software complexity.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Vector processors on the other hand are designed to issue computations of variable length for an arbitrary count, n, and thus require very little setup, and no cleanup.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Even compared to those SIMD ISAs which have masks (but no `setvl` instruction), Vector processors produce much more compact code because they do not need to perform explicit mask calculation to cover the last few elements (illustrated below).
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] One additional potential complication: some RISC ISAs do not have a "min" instruction, needing instead to use a branch or scalar predicated compare.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] It is clear how predicated SIMD at least merits the term "vector capable", because it can cope with variable-length vectors by using predicate masks.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The final evolving step to a "true" vector ISA, however, is to not have any evidence in the ISA *at all* of a SIMD width, leaving that entirely up to the hardware.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] For Cray-style vector ISAs such as RVV, an instruction called "setvl" (set vector length) is used.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The hardware first defines how many data values it can process in one "vector": this could be either actual registers or it could be an internal loop (the hybrid approach, mentioned above).
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] This maximum amount (the number of hardware "lanes") is termed "MVL" (Maximum Vector Length).
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Note that, as seen in SX-Aurora and Videocore IV, MVL may be an actual hardware lane quantity *or a virtual one*.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] *(Note: As mentioned in the ARM SVE2 Tutorial, programmers **must** not make the mistake of assuming a fixed vector width: consequently MVL is not a quantity that the programmer needs to know.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] ARM refers to this technique as "vector length agnostic" programming in its tutorials on SVE2.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Below is the Cray-style vector assembler for the same SIMD style loop, above.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Where the SIMD variant hard-coded both the width (4) into the creation of the mask *and* in the SIMD width (load32x4 etc.) the vector ISA equivalents have no such limit.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] This makes vector programs both portable, Vendor Independent, and future-proof.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Where with predicated SIMD the mask bitlength is limited to that which may be held in a scalar (or special mask) register, vector ISA's mask registers have no such limitation.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Cray-I vectors could be just over 1,000 elements (in 1977).
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Thus it can be seen, very clearly, how vector ISAs reduce the number of instructions.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Also note, that just like the predicated SIMD variant, the pointers to x and y are advanced by t0 times four because they both point to 32 bit data, but that n is decremented by straight t0.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Compared to the fixed-size SIMD assembler there is very little apparent difference: x and y are advanced by hard-coded constant 16, n is decremented by a hard-coded 4, so initially it is hard to appreciate the significance.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The difference comes in the realisation that the vector hardware could be capable of doing 4 simultaneous operations, or 64, or 10,000, it would be the exact same vector assembler for all of them *and there would still be no SIMD cleanup code*.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Even compared to the predicate-capable SIMD, it is still more compact, clearer, more elegant and uses less resources.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Not only is it a much more compact program (saving on L1 Cache size), but as previously mentioned, the vector version can issue far more data processing to the ALUs, again saving power because Instruction Decode and Issue can sit idle.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Additionally, the number of elements going in to the function can start at zero.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] This sets the vector length to zero, which effectively disables all vector instructions, turning them into no-ops, at runtime.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Thus, unlike non-predicated SIMD, even when there are no elements to process there is still no wasted cleanup code, or preamble: not even when n=0.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] In the IBM 3090 an additional benefit (further reduction in instruction count) was achieved.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The `VLVCU` instruction would not only set the Vector Count Length (`VCT`) but it would then subtract the new Vector Length from the Scalar register *and* update a Condition Code that the Branch could test.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Further, both the Vector-Load and Vector-Store instructions could perform the update of the address registers, saving on explicit instructions to perform address-calculations that *in effect* had already been done, behind the scenes, when loading/storing each element of the Vector.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Post-update modes are added to Vectorised versions of Load-with-Update and Store-with-Update, again saving on the need for a separate instruction for address computation when the CPU's Load/Store internals has already done it.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Note again that as with the IBM 370 example: the Vector y address is updated by the Store-with-Update, not a Load-with-Update.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The Power ISA CTR register is used for the total count instead of a scalar register, and the `sv.bc/CTR` instruction performs the reduction of CTR by the current Vector Length (VL) followed by testing CTR for being zero and branching if it is not.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The approach is different but achieves the same end-result as the IBM 3090: a significant compacting of instructions that are already considered highly compact. a RISC-V Vector DAXPY inner loop example is 10 instructions, where Libre-SOC and IBM 370 as shown above are both 6: a 40% reduction.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] This example starts with an algorithm which involves reduction.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Here, an accumulator (y) is used to sum up all the values in the array, x.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] "y" starts at zero, 32 bit integers are loaded one at a time into r1, added to y, and the address of the array "x" moved on to the next element in the array.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] SIMD by design is incapable of doing arithmetic operations "inter-element".
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Element 0 of one SIMD register may be added to Element 0 of another register, but Element 0 may **not** be added to anything **other** than another Element 0.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] This places some severe limitations on potential implementations.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] but with 4-wide SIMD being incapable **by design** of adding `x[0]+x[1]` for example, things go rapidly downhill just as they did with the general case of using SIMD for general-purpose IAXPY loops.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] To sum the four partial results, two-wide SIMD can be used, followed by a single scalar add, to finally produce the answer, but, frequently, the data must be transferred out of dedicated SIMD registers before the last scalar computation can be performed.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Even with a general loop (n not fixed), the only way to use 4-wide SIMD is to assume four separate "streams", each offset by four elements.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Finally, the four partial results have to be summed.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The problems compound as the SIMD hardware width increases (an entirely new set of instruction is introduced), and, worse, some instructions to do Horizontal-sum such as the AMD XOP_instruction_set, were *removed* after a few years.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Aside from the size of the program and the complexity, an additional potential problem arises if floating-point computation is involved: the fact that the values are not being summed in strict order (four partial results) could result in rounding errors.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Vector instruction sets have arithmetic reduction operations *built-in* to the ISA.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The code when n is larger than the maximum vector length is not that much more complex, and is a similar pattern to the first example ("IAXPY").
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] The simplicity of the algorithm is stark in comparison to SIMD.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Again, just as with the IAXPY example, the algorithm is length-agnostic (even on Embedded implementations where maximum vector length could be only one).
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Implementations in hardware may, if they are certain that the right answer will be produced, perform the reduction in parallel.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Some vector ISAs offer a parallel reduction mode as an explicit option, for when the programmer knows that any potential rounding errors do not matter, and low latency is critical.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] This example again highlights a key critical fundamental difference between true vector processors and those SIMD processors, including most commercial GPUs, which are inspired by features of vector processors.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Compared to any SIMD processor claiming to be a vector processor, the order of magnitude reduction in program size is almost shocking.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] Whilst from the reduction example it can be seen that, aside from permute instructions, SIMD by definition avoids inter-lane operations entirely (element 0 can only be added to another element 0), vector processors tackle this head-on.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] What programmers are forced to do in software (using shuffle and other tricks, to swap data into the right "lane") vector processors must do in hardware, automatically.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p01] These stark differences are what distinguishes a vector processor from one that has SIMD.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p02] Introduced in ARM SVE2 and RISC-V RVV is the concept of speculative sequential vector loads.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p02] ARM SVE2 has a special register named "First Fault Register", where RVV modifies (truncates) the vector length (VL).
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p02] The basic principle of ffirst is to attempt a large sequential vector load, but to allow the hardware to arbitrarily truncate the *actual* amount loaded to either the amount that would succeed without raising a memory fault or simply to an amount (greater than zero) that is most convenient.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p02] The important factor is that *subsequent* instructions are notified or may determine exactly how many loads actually succeeded, using that quantity to only carry out work on the data that has actually been loaded.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p02] This begins to hint at the reason why ffirst is so innovative, and is best illustrated by memcpy or strcpy when implemented with standard 128-bit non-predicated non-ffirst SIMD.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p02] For IBM POWER9 the number of hand-optimised instructions to implement strncpy is in excess of 240.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p02] By contrast, the same strncpy routine in hand-optimised RVV assembler is a mere 22 instructions.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p02] The above SIMD example could potentially fault and fail at the end of memory, due to attempts to read too many values: it could also cause significant numbers of page or misaligned faults by similarly crossing over boundaries.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p02] Additionally, the hardware may choose to use the opportunity to end any given loop iteration's memory reads *exactly* on a page boundary (avoiding a costly second TLB lookup), with speculative execution preparing the next virtual memory page whilst data is still being processed in the current loop.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p02] All of this is determined by the hardware, not the program itself.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p02] Let ***r*** be the vector speed ratio and ***f*** be the vectorization ratio.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p02] If the time taken for the vector unit to add an array of 64 numbers is 10 times faster than its equivalent scalar counterpart, r = 10.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p02] Also, if the total number of operations in a program is 100, out of which only 10 are scalar (after vectorization), then f = 0.9, i.e., 90% of the work is done by the vector unit.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p02] So, even if the performance of the vector unit is very high ( $r=\infty$ ) there is a speedup less than $1/(1-f)$ , which suggests that the ratio ***f*** is crucial to the performance.
[src:vector-processor/vector-processor-p02] This ratio depends on the efficiency of the compilation like adjacency of the elements in memory.
